Jan Bos ( born 29 March 1975 ) is a Dutch speedskater and sprint cyclist . In the late 1990s he was known as one of the world’s leading distance skaters, and he has several European and World titles on the boards. He has also won three gold medals in the 1500 meters for the 1998 Winter Olympics in Nagano, Japan, where he became the fastest man of all time. In 2007, he won the European Championship title in the sprint. Born in Assen, Groningen , Bos was originally a speed skater, but in 2002 switched to the track bike.

A finite difference is a mathematical expression of the form . If a finite difference is divided by , one gets an expression known as a derivative. Differentiating a polynomial of order is a straightforward matter of applying the Leibniz Rule and a finite difference. The problem arises when one attempts to differentiate a polynomial of order or higher. The most common approach is to use Taylor series. Taylor series has an advantage of being very easy to implement on a computer but, on the other hand, it can take quite a few terms to approximate higher order polynomials sufficiently well.

The picometre ( international spelling as used by the International Bureau of Weights and Measures ; SI symbol : pm ) is a unit of length. 1 Definition and abbreviation
Definition and abbreviation[edit]
The name of the picometre was coined as a contraction of picosecond metre (pm). In some older works the symbol is sometimes seen as being μμ; this is, however, incorrect. The correct symbol is ppm. 10−12 metres or 1/1000 of an angstrom. The picometre is also one-trillionth of a metre, and 2.78×10 −10 inches or 1/27.8 millionth of an inch.

The Quirinal Hill (; ;  ) is one of the Seven Hills of Rome, at the north-east of the city center. It is the location of the official residence of the Italian head of state, who resides in the Quirinal Palace; by metonymy "the Quirinal" has come to stand for the Italian president. The Quirinal Palace has an extension of 1.2 million square feet.History According to Roman legend, the Quirinal Hill was the site of a small village of the Sabines, and king Titus Tatius would have lived there after the peace between Romans and Sabines.

Samuel de Champlain ( ; c. 13 August 1567 – 25 December 1635 ) was a French colonist , navigator and cartographer who played a prominent role in the establishment and settlement of New France . Champlain made several journeys to Acadia to assist in establishing the settlement of Port-Royal in Acadia, where he also made a permanent home. He established a fur trading outpost, which he called "The Habitation." In 1608, he returned to Quebec to take command as the second in command to the French colony of Canada under Pierre Dugua de Mons, the Sieur de Mons.

Optical rotation, also known as polarization rotation or circular birefringence, is the rotation of the orientation of the plane of polarization about the optical axis of linearly polarized light as it travels through certain materials. Circular birefringence and circular dichroism are the manifestations of optical activity. Optical activity occurs only in chiral materials, those lacking microscopic mirror symmetry. Unlike other sources of birefringence which alter a beam's state of polarization, optical activity can be observed in fluids. This can include gases or solutions of chiral molecules such as sugars, molecules with helical secondary structure such as some proteins, and also chiral liquid crystals.

Ski jumping is a winter sport in which competitors aim to achieve the farthest jump after sliding down on their skis, from a raised ramp, or in the case of the team events, from a four hill team event, the farthest jump for a team after the four competitors have taken their turns on their skis. It is the second oldest and second most popular Nordic skiing event, second only to cross country skiing, which is also known as "Nordic combined," because it includes the 10 km classical cross country race and the jump.

Berchtesgaden is a municipality in the district Berchtesgadener Land , Bavaria , in southeastern Germany , near the border with Austria . It is famous for its natural beauty as it lies in the Bavarian Alps , and it is home to the Watzmann , Germany's third highest mountain. Berchtesgaden is located in the German Alps and is a famous tourist destination with many recreational opportunities. It is also an important skiing center, with alpine skiing at the Jenneralpe, cross-country skiing and hiking on the Jennerweisskarspitz, and the Königsseilbahn funicular railway. It is a gateway to the Berchtesgaden National Park and to the Hohe Salzburg mountain and the Watzmann massif.

Eleusine coracana , or finger millet , also known as ragi in India , kodo in Nepal , is an annual crop grown in India and other countries in tropical and subtropical regions, including China, Africa and Indonesia . Eleusine coracana - Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
Finger millet is believed to have originated in eastern and central Africa from the wild grass species eleusine coracana , which was domesticated in around 5000 BC. The domesticated plant has been used for centuries as a source of food in Asia and Africa . The millet grows to a height of one to two metres (3.3 - 6.6 ft).

The French and Indian War (1754–1763) was a theater of the Seven Years' War, which pitted the North American colonies of the British Empire against those of the French, each side being supported by various Native American tribes. At the start of the war, the French colonies had a population of roughly 60,000 settlers, compared with 2 million in the British colonies. The outnumbered French particularly depended on the natives.Two years into the French and Indian War, in 1756, Great Britain declared war on France, beginning the worldwide Seven Years' War.

Norwich is a town in Windsor County, in the U.S. state of Vermont. The population was 3,612 at the 2020 census. Home to some of the state of Vermont's wealthiest residents, the municipality is a commuter town for nearby Hanover, New Hampshire across the Connecticut River. The town is part of the Dresden School District, the first interstate school district in the United States, signed into law by President John F. Kennedy. The town contains the Norwich Mid-Century Modern Historic District.History The boundaries of Norwich were established on July 4, 1761, when Governor Benning Wentworth of New Hampshire defined the boundaries of townships in Vermont.

In art history , literature and cultural studies , Orientalism is the imitation or depiction of aspects in the Eastern world or cultures, as perceived in the West (Europe, Australia, and America). In particular, Orientalist painting was a style of its own in the 19th century, following the expansion of the Ottoman Empire and culminating in works like Ingres’ The Turkish Bath (1862) and Matisse ‘s orientalist period (1898-1920) during which he produced the Dance (1910), Odalisque in Red Trousers (1925) and many others.

Byzantine troops personally led by Constantine repel him, and re-occupy the walls. Tornikios is forced to withdraw, while his followers start to abandon him. Finally, he is captured at a church in Boulgarophygon (modern Turkey), and is publicly blinded.

Jochem Simon Uytdehaage ( born 9 July 1976 ) is a Dutch former long track speed skater who won two world championships in the sprint. He was the world record holder for the sprint and the 500 m and 200 m world records holder. In addition, he was world champion in sprint, silver medallist in Olympic team pursuit, silver medalist in team pursuit 2006 Olympics, silver medalist in the world championship team pursuit, bronze medal in the world championship team pursuit. He is a world record holder with the team pursuit in 2004 and with the relay team in 1999 and 2005.

ext3 , or third extended filesystem , is a journaled file system that is commonly used by the Linux kernel for all Linux file systems. It is supported by the Linux kernel since version 2.0.0. It was designed and implemented at SGI by Brian Paul, who is known as the "Father of ext". It is used by default in most major Linux distributions. ext3 was superseded by ext4 in the Linux kernel since version 2.6.28. ext3 remains the default file system until version 2.6.30, when ext4 became the new default for the first time.

Charles XIV John ( ; born Jean Bernadotte ; 26 January 1763 – 8 March 1844 ) was King of Sweden and Norway from 1818 until his death. He also reigned as duke of Schleswig and Holstein, as well as prince of Pontecorvo. The Bernadotte family was of French extraction, having migrated to the countryside of Pau in the south of France in the 17th century from the village of Bernadotte, now known as Bernod, in the département of Ariège, in the Massif central of France. There, Jean's father Jean Henri was a miller, who worked his land as a farmer.

Solidarity Electoral Action (, AWS) was a political coalition in Poland. Since 1997, its official name has been Akcja Wyborcza Solidarność Prawicy (AWSP) or Electoral Action Solidarity of the Right. Ruch Społeczny AWS (RS AWS), or Social Movement for Electoral Action Solidarity, was the political arm of the Solidarity trade union and was formerly the leading party within AWS.BackgroundAWS was formed in 1996 as a coalition of over 30 parties, uniting liberal, conservative and Christian-democratic forces. Marian Krzaklewski was its first chairman. In 1997 the coalition was joined by RS AWS, and by the Freedom Union.

Wellfleet is a town in Barnstable County , Massachusetts , United States , and is located halfway between the `` upper'' and ''lower'' Cape regions. The population was 2625 at the 2000 census. Originally part of Eastham, Wellfleet was settled in 1653 and was incorporated on May 14, 1653. Wellfleet is the last town on Cape Cod before heading out to sea . It lies at the outer limit of Cape Cod Bay and along the Atlantic Ocean . It is bordered by the towns of Truro to the north, Eastham to the northeast, and Provincetown to the east.

Robert I Estienne (; 15037 September 1559), known as Robertus Stephanus in Latin and sometimes referred to as Robert Stephens, was a 16th-century printer and classical scholar in Paris. He was the proprietor of the Estienne print shop after the death of his father Henri Estienne, the founder of the Estienne printing firm. Estienne published and republished many classical texts as well as Greek and Latin translations of the Bible. Known as "Printer to the King" in Latin, Hebrew, and Greek, Estienne's most prominent work was the Thesaurus linguae latinae which is considered to be the foundation of modern Latin lexicography.

The National Botanic Gardens (Irish: Garraithe Náisiúnta na Lus) is a botanical garden in Glasnevin, 5 km north-west of Dublin city centre, Ireland. The 19.5 hectares are situated between Glasnevin Cemetery and the River Tolka where it forms part of the river's floodplain.The gardens were founded in 1795 by the Dublin Society (later the Royal Dublin Society) and are today in State ownership through the Office of Public Works. They house approximately 20,000 living plants and many millions of dried plant specimens. There are several architecturally notable greenhouses.

Alpaca, llama, vicu�a, guanaco, and camelid are members of the family Camelidae, which includes the camel. Divorce (also known as dissolution of marriage) is the process of terminating a marriage or marital union. Divorce usually entails the canceling or reorganizing of the legal duties and responsibilities of marriage, thus dissolving the bonds of matrimony between a married couple under the rule of law of the particular country or state. Divorce laws vary considerably around the world, but in most countries, divorce requires the sanction of a court or other authority in a legal process, which may involve issues of distribution of property, child custody, alimony (spousal support), child visitation / access, parenting time, child support, and division of debt.

Year 1532 ( MDXXXII ) was a leap year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. 1532 is known as the Year of the Death of the Eight Popes in Roman Catholic tradition, because in that year, sixteen days after Pope Adrian VI died, Pope Clement VII was elected, and died twenty days later, followed by cardinals electing Pope Paul III, who was then followed in the following year by Pope Julius III. These events are sometimes remembered in Roman Catholicism as the Year of Seven Popes, because Paul III was not elected in 1532.

Renate Titzia Groenewold (born 8 October 1976) is a Dutch former long track speed skater and road bicycle racer.Groenewold has won several Dutch Championships. In 1999, 2002 and 2003 she won the Dutch allround championship. At the European Allround Championships she has won various medals. Five times she came in third in the overall ranking. In 2005, she won the silver medal which was her best result at the European Championships. In 2001, she also came in third in the overall ranking on the World Allround Championships, which she won in 2004.Besides participating in the all-round championships Groenewold has participated in the championships for individual distances.

GNU Privacy Guard (GnuPG or GPG) is a free-software replacement for Symantec's PGP cryptographic software suite. The software is compliant with RFC 4880, the IETF standards-track specification of OpenPGP. Modern versions of PGP are interoperable with GnuPG and other OpenPGP-compliant systems.GnuPG is part of the GNU Project and received major funding from the German government in 1999.Overview GnuPG is a hybrid-encryption software program because it uses a combination of conventional symmetric-key cryptography for speed, and public-key cryptography for ease of secure key exchange, typically by using the recipient's public key to encrypt a session key which is used only once.

Toktar Ongarbayuly Aubakirov ( ( Toqtar Oñğarbaiūly Äubäkırov ) , , born on 27 July 1946 ) is a retired Kazakhstani ice hockey goaltender who was active for Metallurg Novokuznetsk from the 1970s up to and including the 1980s. He is the most capped international player in Kazakhstani hockey history and was the first to play internationally. He had also been the headcoach and general secretary of the Kazakhstani national ice hockey team. He is the first ever inductee into both the IIHF Hall of Fame and the Kazakhstan Hockey Federation Hall of Fame, both of which took place in 2009.

Slapstick is a style of humor involving exaggerated physical activity that exceeds the boundaries of normal physical comedy . Slapstick often involves violence, and can be rude, gross, or tasteless, but it is generally regarded as non-harmful. Historically, slapstick has been a staple of vaudeville and burlesque , as well as British , American , and French stage comedies . It has also found its way into popular media such as film (from the 1890s), radio (from the 1920s) and television (1950s), particularly in cartoons .

Uracil  (symbol U or Ura) is one of the four nucleobases in the nucleic acid RNA that are represented by the letters A, G, C and U. The others are adenine (A), cytosine (C), and guanine (G). In RNA, uracil binds to adenine via two hydrogen bonds. In DNA, the uracil nucleobase is replaced by thymine. Uracil is a demethylated form of thymine.Uracil is a common and naturally occurring pyrimidine derivative. The name "uracil" was coined in 1885 by the German chemist Robert Behrend, who was attempting to synthesize derivatives of uric acid.

The governor of Montana is the head of government of Montana and the commander-in-chief of the state 's military forces. The current office holder is the incumbent governor, Republican Matt Rosendale, who is currently in his first term in office. The office of governor was created in 1889. The governor of Montana is elected for a term of four years and may not serve more than two consecutive terms. [1]

Robert Sanderson Mulliken  (June 7, 1896 – October 31, 1986) was an American physicist and chemist, primarily responsible for the early development of molecular orbital theory, i.e. the elaboration of the molecular orbital method of computing the structure of molecules. Mulliken received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1966 and the Priestley Medal in 1983.Early yearsRobert Mulliken was born in Newburyport, Massachusetts. His father, Samuel Parsons Mulliken, was a professor of organic chemistry at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. As a child, Robert Mulliken learned the name and botanical classification of plants and, in general, had an excellent, but selective, memory.

Events <onlyinclude>January–June  January 17 – The Treaty of Königsberg is signed, establishing an alliance between Charles X Gustav of Sweden and Frederick William, Elector of Brandenburg. The 1988 United States presidential election was the 51st quadrennial presidential election , held on Tuesday , November 8 , 1988. George Bush , the Republican Governor of Texas , and the 1988 Republican presidential nominee , won the election . He was sworn in as President of the United States on Inauguration Day 1989 , succeeding the first President Bush (George H.W. Bush). Bush defeated Democratic Governor of Massachusetts Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts , the Democratic presidential nominee , and Clint Eastwood as the Reform Party candidate . Independent candidate , Texas Congressman Ron Paul was a Libertarian .

Uracil ( symbol U or Ura ) is one of the four nucleobases in the nucleic acid RNA that are used to code for proteins with a sequence. Uracil occurs in the ribose (ribose) -phosphate-ribose (ribose) chain, which is one of the basic elements of RNA. It is an analog of thymine, which is one of the two bases of DNA ( the other is cytosine). It differs in that an oxygen atom in the carbonyl group (in the 5th position of the aromatic ring ) replaced by hydrogen. As a base, uracil pairs in the formation of the base pair with adenine .

Casimir IV ( in full Casimir IV Andrew Jagiellon ; ; Lithuanian : ; 30 November 1427 – 7 June 1492) was King of Poland from the Piast dynasty between 1447 and his death. He was crowned King of Bohemia (the only monarch crowned in Prague, outside of the capital city) in 1458 but he lost the throne in 1471. He was also elected Grand Duke of Lithuania in 1440, however he had to wait 17 years for election confirmation; he eventually ruled both Poland and Lithuania from 1454 until 1458.

Jan Bos (born 29 March 1975) is a Dutch speedskater and sprint cyclist. In the late 1990s he was world champion in speed skating and he competed in the 1998 and 2002 Winter Olympics.Speed skaterIn 1998 Bos both became the world champion sprint and won the silver medal that year in the 1000 meter sprint during the Winter Olympics in Nagano. He won the silver medal on that same distance in Salt Lake City.He competed at the 2004 Summer Olympics in Athens in the team sprint track cycling event, together with his brother Theo Bos, who won the silver at the individual sprint, and Teun Mulder.

Major League Baseball (MLB) is a professional baseball organization and the oldest major professional sports league in the world. , a total of 30 teams play in Major League Baseball—15 teams in the National League (NL) and 15 in the American League (AL)—with 29 in the United States and 1 in Canada. The NL and AL were formed in 1876 and 1901, respectively. Beginning in 1903, the two leagues signed the National Agreement and cooperated but remained legally separate entities until 2000 when they merged into a single organization led by the Commissioner of Baseball.

The African clawed frog ( Xenopus laevis , also known as the xenopus , African clawed toad , African claw-toed toad , and platanna , is a relatively large aquatic frog ( to 18 cm ) native to southern Africa, and is one of the most important models in biological research. It is used widely in embryonic development and stem cell studies. It can be kept in a 20 US gal ( 80 L ) aquarium at room temperature, but it is more commonly maintained at 20 - 27 �C. The African clawed frog is widely used as a food source in Africa.

In the performing arts , a scenario ( , ; from Italian : `` that which is pinned to the wall,'' via Latin :  from French : scenario , from Italian ) is an outline of the events that are going to take place in a play or film , or the like. Jon Howard Appleton ( January 4 , 1939 – January 30 , 2022 ) was an American composer , an influential experimental musician , and a teacher at The New School for Social Research in Manhattan . He has been called "a pioneer of American electronic music " and a "master of electronic music". Appleton was born in New Haven, Connecticut, where his mother was an organist and choir director . At age five, he began piano lessons. By 1957, he had studied composition with Otto Luening at Columbia University and with Henry Cowell in Connecticut.

"Coven"  usually refers to a group or gathering of witches. The word "coven" (from Anglo-Norman covent, cuvent, from Old French covent, from Latin conventum = convention) remained largely unused in English until 1921 when Margaret Murray promoted the idea that all witches across Europe met in groups of thirteen which they called "covens".NeopaganismIn Wicca and other similar forms of neopagan witchcraft, such as Stregheria and Feri, a coven is a gathering or community of witches, like an affinity group, engagement group, or small covenant group.

Greyhound racing is an organized , competitive sport in which greyhounds are raced around a track . There are two forms of the sport, one with the dogs chasing a lure ( lure coursing ) and one with the dogs actually chasing each other ( coursing ). Coursing is a combination of two French words, cour (meaning course, or run) and chasse (meaning pursuit or chase). Different breeds of dogs have been bred to use their natural running and hunting skills in a variety of events. It is estimated that more than two million spectators in Britain attended greyhound races in 2011.

Johan August Arfwedson (12 January 1792 – 28 October 1841) was a  Swedish chemist who discovered the chemical element lithium in 1817 by isolating it as a salt.Life and work Arfwedson belonged to a wealthy bourgeois family, the son of the wholesale merchant and factory owner Jacob Arfwedson and his spouse, Anna Elisabeth Holtermann. The younger Arfwedson matriculated as a student at the University of Uppsala in 1803 (at the time, matriculating at a young age was common for aristocratic and wealthy students), completed a degree in Law in 1809 and a second degree in mineralogy in 1812.

Mariner 10 was an American robotic space probe launched by NASA on 3 November 1973, to fly by the planets Mercury and Venus. It was the first spacecraft to perform flybys of multiple planets.Mariner 10 was launched approximately two years after Mariner 9 and was the last spacecraft in the Mariner program. (Mariner 11 and Mariner 12 were allocated to the Voyager program and redesignated Voyager 1 and Voyager 2. )The mission objectives were to measure Mercury's environment, atmosphere, surface, and body characteristics and to make similar investigations of Venus.

Sir Richard Newdigate, 2nd Baronet, records the events in his diary.

A shank is a type of knot that is used to shorten a rope or take up slack, such as the sheepshank. The sheepshank knot is not stable. The foreign relations of Albania are its relations with other governments and peoples. Foreign relations are conducted through the Ministry of Foreign Affairs in Tirana. The current minister is Olta Xhaçka. The current Ambassador to the United Nations is Besiana Kadare.Albania is a sovereign country in Southern Europe and the Mediterranean that declared its independence on 28 November 1912. Its foreign policy has maintained a policy of complementarism by trying to have friendly relations with all countries. Since the collapse of Communism in 1990, Albania has extended its responsibilities and position in European and international affairs, supporting and establishing friendly relations with other nations around the world.

Frederick James Prinze (born Frederick Karl Pruetzel; June 22, 1954 – January 29, 1977) was an American stand-up comedian and actor. Prinze was the star of the NBC-TV sitcom Chico and the Man from 1974 until his suicide in 1977, when he shot himself in the head at the young age of 22. Prinze was the father of actor Freddie Prinze Jr.Early lifePrinze was born Frederick Karl Pruetzel (German spelling: Prützel) at Saint Clare's Hospital in Manhattan, New York City the son of Edward Karl Pruetzel and Maria de Gracia Pruetzel (née Graniela y Ramirez).

Cooking bananas are banana cultivars in the genus Musa whose fruits are generally used in cooking . They may be boiled, roasted, steamed, baked or fried like chips. They are an important part of many traditional recipes and are frequently eaten at lunchtime, for example in Ghana , Nigeria and Cameroon. The cooking banana is not related to plantain , another widely eaten tropical banana. The two are easily confused in North American and European cuisine, though the names plantain , platano or platanier, as well as the terms green banana and raw banana, may be used for both in various places.

McLean Hospital  (formerly known as Somerville Asylum and Charlestown Asylum) is a psychiatric hospital in Belmont, Massachusetts. It is noted for its clinical staff expertise and neuroscience research and is also known for the large number of famous people who have been treated there. McLean maintains the world's largest neuroscientific and psychiatric research program in a private hospital. It is the largest psychiatric facility of Harvard Medical School, an affiliate of Massachusetts General Hospital, and part of Mass General Brigham, which also includes Brigham and Women's Hospital.History McLean was founded in 1811 in a section of Charlestown, Massachusetts that is now a part of Somerville, Massachusetts.

English Renaissance theatre, also known as Renaissance English theatre and Elizabethan theatre, refers to the theatre of England between 1558 and 1642.This is the style of the plays of William Shakespeare, Christopher Marlowe and Ben Jonson.BackgroundThe term English Renaissance theatre encompasses the period between 1562—following a performance of Gorboduc, the first English play using blank verse, at the Inner Temple during the Christmas season of 1561—and the ban on theatrical plays enacted by the English Parliament in 1642.The phrase Elizabethan theatre is sometimes improperly used to mean English Renaissance theatre, although in a strict sense "Elizabethan" only refers to the period of Queen Elizabeth's reign (1558–1603).

Alappuzha district , is one of the 14 districts in the state of Kerala in India . It was formed as Alleppey District on August 17,1957. It was formed by combining Kottayam and Kollam districts. Later it was split into Kollam and Alapuzha districts on 1 November 1983. Alleppey is known as the Venice of the East and is famous for backwaters and houseboats. It also has a few good temples which are worth visiting. The temples here are very beautiful and famous and one can be mesmerized by their beautiful architecture and ambiance. Aroor is situated 6 kms. north-west of Alappuzha.

A domain name is an identification string that defines a realm of administrative autonomy, authority or control within the Internet. Domain names are used in various networking contexts and for application-specific naming and addressing purposes. In general, a domain name identifies a network domain, or it represents an Internet Protocol (IP) resource, such as a personal computer used to access the Internet, a server computer hosting a website, or the web site itself or any other service communicated via the Internet. As of 2017, 330.6 million domain names had been registered.Domain names are formed by the rules and procedures of the Domain Name System (DNS).

A lever ( or ) is a simple machine consisting of a beam or rigid rod pivoted at a fixed hinge, or fulcrum. A lever is a rigid body capable of rotating on a point on itself. On the basis of the locations of fulcrum, load and effort, the lever is divided into three types. Also, leverage is mechanical advantage gained in a system. It is one of the six simple machines identified by Renaissance scientists. A lever amplifies an input force to provide a greater output force, which is said to provide leverage.

Melvin Kranzberg ( November 22 , 1917 – December 6 , 1995 ) was an American historian , and professor emeritus at Georgia Institute of Technology who was an early and prominent historian of technology and technology policy . [2] [3] His most famous work, a series of lectures entitled “Five Laws of Technology”, is taught in many universities [4] and has been translated into over a dozen languages. [2] Kranzberg’s most famous contribution to the study of technology was his essay, “Laws of Media Technology,” which was published in the journal Science, Progress, and Sustainable Development .

Broca 's area , or the Broca area ( , also , ) , is a region in the frontal portion of the motor cortex of the frontal lobe in the left hemisphere of the brain that has been implicated in the production of language in humans . Broca's area was identified in 1861 by Paul Broca , a neurologist and anthropologist . Broca was able to demonstrate a link between speech impairment and specific brain injury . Because of Broca's discoveries, this region of the brain is now considered a critical area of the brain for human language production .

A noble savage is a literary stock character who embodies the concept of the indigene, outsider, wild human, an "other" who has not been "corrupted" by civilization, and therefore symbolizes humanity's innate goodness. Besides appearing in many works of fiction and philosophy, the stereotype was also heavily employed in early anthropological works.In English, the phrase first appeared in the 17th century in John Dryden's heroic play The Conquest of Granada (1672), wherein it was used in reference to newly created man. "Savage" at that time could mean "wild beast" as well as "wild man".

Year 994 (CMXCIV) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  September 15 – Battle of the Orontes: Fatimid forces, under Turkish general Manjutakin (also the governor of Damascus), besiege Apamea (modern Syria). Emperor Basil II sends a Byzantine expeditionary army, led by Dux Michael Bourtzes, to relieve the city in alliance with the Hamdanid Dynasty. Manjutakin defeats with his forces the Hamdanids, and attacks the Byzantine force in the rear. The Byzantine army panics and flees, losing some 5,000 men in the process.

Gerard Pieter Hendrik van Velde (born 30 November 1971) is a Dutch retired speed skater who specialised in sprinting. He won an Olympic gold medal in 2002.BiographyVan Velde was considered the best Dutch sprinter during the early 1990s, but did not manage to win a medal in either the 1992 or 1994 Winter Olympics. The 1992 Games were particularly frustrating, as he missed a bronze medal by only one-hundredth of a second.During the late 1990s, clap skates became standard in Olympic competition. Van Velde had such difficulty adjusting to the techniques required with these new skates that he retired from skating and became a car salesman.

In mathematics , two sets are said to be disjoint sets if they have no element in common . Equivalently, a set of points is disjoint from another set of points if the points from the two sets do not coincide, and the same is true for non-empty sets. If each point or set is taken from a universal set, the condition is also referred to as pairwise disjoint sets and is denoted by [1]
If A is any set, then A ∪ ∅=A and ∅=∅. The empty set is always disjoint from every set.

Year 1181 ( MCLXXXI ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This year marked the beginning of the Anarchy, a civil war between the rival kings and their supporters, in the Kingdom of England , which lasted through 1183–1185. The Anarchy was precipitated when Henry II of England and his wife Eleanor, returned from his crusades to discover that his son, the king's heir and his preferred successor to his throne, was in open revolt with his younger brother Richard .

Year 1391 ( MCCCXCI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. 1453 – Siege of Belgrade: Ottoman Sultan Mehmed II Fatih captured the capital of Serbian Empire, after a six-week siege. The Siege of Belgrade was a siege of the Hungarian and Croatian held city of Belgrade that took place from 22 July 1456 to 29 August 1456. It was the main event of a three-year conflict between the Ottoman Empire and the Kingdom of Hungary and its allies. The Ottomans besieged the city from three sides, and the Hungarian army was commanded by the palatine János Hunyadi.

Arthrobacter ( from the Greek , `` jointed small stick ” ) is a genus of bacteria that is commonly found in freshwater, soil and sewage. A. sp. was first discovered by John G. Merrill in 1951 and named as the organism. Most of the bacteria in the genus are Gram-negative and obligate aerobes. They are rod-shaped. A. arsenicoxidans was first discovered in 2000. The type species of this genus is A. ammoniagenens. ## Arthrobacter species

Species of Arthrobacter are Gram-negative, facultative anaerobic, catalase negative and rod-shaped aerobes.

Adnams is a regional brewery founded in 1872 in Southwold , Suffolk , England , by George and Ernest Adnams. The firm's brewery in Southwold, Suffolk , is the company's sole brewing location. The company also owns two hotels: The Swan in Southwold and the Spa Hotel, in nearby Aldeburgh , and the Ghost Ship pub in Ipswich . The company's core portfolio comprises Adnams' and Ghost Ship lagers, Adnams' Ghost Ship and Broadside bitters and the Broadside 4.2% lager. They also make a range of spirits from vodka to gin.

Reginald Joseph Mitchell CBE , FRAeS , ( 20 May 189511 June 1937 ) was a British aircraft designer who emigrated to the US in 1918 and is best known for his designs of aeroplanes, among them the first of the Spitfire fighters. He moved to the United States and joined the Supermarine Aviation Works of West Wittering, England, which produced aircraft for the Supermarine Aviation Company. When that company merged with the Vickers Aviation Department to form Vickers (Aviation), Ltd. , Mitchell went with the company's new aircraft division. He designed the S. 6B, winner of the 1922 Schneider Trophy.

Charles XV also Carl (Carl Ludvig Eugen); Swedish: Karl XV and Norwegian: Karl IV (3 May 1826 – 18 September 1872) was King of Sweden (Charles XV) and Norway, there often referred to accurately as Charles IV, from 1859 until his death in 1872. Though known as King Charles XV in Sweden (and also on contemporary Norwegian coins), he was actually the ninth Swedish king by that name, as his predecessor Charles IX (reigned 1604–1611) had adopted a numeral according to a fictitious history of Sweden.

An oak is a tree or shrub in the genus Quercus (; Latin "oak tree") of the beech family, Fagaceae. There are approximately 500 extant species of oaks. The common name "oak" also appears in the names of species in related genera, notably Lithocarpus (stone oaks), as well as in those of unrelated species such as Grevillea robusta (silky oaks) and the Casuarinaceae (she-oaks). The genus Quercus is native to the Northern Hemisphere, and includes deciduous and evergreen species extending from cool temperate to tropical latitudes in the Americas, Asia, Europe, and North Africa.

Anne Boleyn (;  1501 – 19 May 1536) was Queen of England from 1533 to 1536, as the second wife of King Henry VIII. The circumstances of her marriage and of her execution by beheading for treason and other charges made her a key figure in the political and religious upheaval that marked the start of the English Reformation. Anne was the daughter of Thomas Boleyn, 1st Earl of Wiltshire, and his wife, Lady Elizabeth Howard, and was educated in the Netherlands and France, largely as a maid of honour to Queen Claude of France.

Bdellovibrio is a genus of Gram-negative , obligate aerobic bacterium . One of the more notable characteristics of this genus is that its members are all parasites. They are able to infect a variety of eukaryotic cells including those found in plants , fungi , and protozoa ; they are able to reproduce in these host cells, without killing them. Some species infect amoebas while others affect fungi and plants. It has been noted that many of the species in this genus are highly host-specific and it is rare to find species that can be found infecting a variety of host species.

The Polish People 's Party ( , PSL ) is an agrarian political party in Poland . It is currently led by Jaroslaw Grudzinski , who also serves as deputy leader of the party. ## History

### Founding

The party was founded as the Polish People's Stronnictwo Rymarza (PSR; Ruralist Party) on 26 March [O.S. 12 March] 1904 in Poznań, with Michal Brudnicki serving as chairman and Julian Slawinski as deputy chairman of the party. In its early years the party mainly represented landowners and agrarian interest groups. It was a conservative-liberal party with a right-liberal ideology.

is the Latin name under which the `` Lamb of God '' is honoured within the Catholic Mass and other forms of Christian worship, particularly by Anglicans, Eastern Christians and Protestants. Christianity is the most popular and the most practised religion in the world with a following of approximately 2.3 billion people globally. It is considered to be an Abrahamic religion, which holds that the Old Testament is scripture, and that belief in Jesus as God is necessary for Salvation. It is generally agreed that the beginnings of Christianity date back to the first few decades after Jesus' death.

The Battle of Trafalgar ( 21 October 1805 ) was a naval engagement between the British Royal Navy and the combined fleets of the Spanish and French empires. Twelve French and Spanish ships were captured and two were sunk and a further 18 ships of the line and four frigates were either damaged or destroyed during the battle. Fifteen thousand French and Spanish casualties were sustained, including death of Admiral Villeneuve. The British Royal Navy lost no ships, but suffered more than a thousand casualties. Vice Admiral Nelson was shot and died shortly after leading the British to victory.

The 9th century BC started the first day of 900 BC and ended the last day of 801 BC. It was a period of great change for several civilizations. In Africa, Carthage is founded by the Phoenicians. A pine is any conifer tree or shrub in the genus Pinus of the family Pinaceae . Pinus is the only genus in the subfamily Pinaceae. There are 115 – 125 species of pine , depending on the system of taxonomy used . The modern English name pine is derived from the Latin word pinus, which was borrowed from Greek pinos, a word of unknown origin . The Ancient Greek name was derived from the Greek root pin-; the old English names for the pine came from the Norse, with a few minor differences, and the modern Scandinavian and Germanic names are all similarly derived.

Lullingstone Roman Villa is a villa built during the Roman occupation of Britain , situated in Lullingstone near the village of Eynsford in Kent . The site is believed to date from about AD 220 to AD 240 and may have remained occupied to the later 4th century, though possibly for lesser periods. It was excavated in the 1940s by O. G. S. Crawford, but the findings from the site are now kept in the British Museum. Roman villas were residences of wealthy Romans, mainly used for holiday retreats and as places for entertainment.

Year 1182 ( MCLXXXII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. March 10 – Philip II of France marries Ingeborg of Denmark, in an attempt to mend fences between the two countries, after Philip's father Louis VII was forced to cede Normandy to England at the Treaty of Rouen, three years earlier. Ingeborg dies 10 days later. July 24 – William II is murdered at Curry Mallet, England. August 14 – Richard the Lionheart is crowned king of England, succeeding his father, Henry II.

The 12th century BC is the period from 1200 to 1101 BC . The Late Bronze Age collapse in the Near East and Aegean is first mentioned by the contemporary Egyptian texts and the Amarna letters of the Pharaoh Akenaten . In the northern hemisphere, it is considered to be at the end of the Early Iron Age in the Ancient Near East, or the Late Bronze Age in mainland Greece and Italy. It coincides with the start of the European Dark Ages and is followed by the Iron Age . In China, the Shang Dynasty is starting to fall apart, to be succeeded by the Western Zhou.

Arthur Andersen LLP was an American holding company based in Chicago. Formerly one of the "Big Five" accounting firms (along with PricewaterhouseCoopers, Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu, Ernst & Young, and KPMG), the company had provided auditing, tax and consulting services to large corporations. By 2001, it had become one of the world's largest multinational corporations.In 2002, the firm voluntarily surrendered its licenses to practice as Certified Public Accountants in the United States after it was found guilty of crimes in the firm's auditing of Enron, an energy corporation based in Texas, which had filed for bankruptcy in 2001.

According to a contemporary account: "An awful fire broke out on the Southwark side of London Bridge; while it was raging, a fire broke out at the other end also and so hemmed in the numerous crowds who had assembled to help the distressed.

Peter Halsten Thorkelson (February 13, 1942 – February 21, 2019), known professionally as Peter Tork, was an American musician, composer, and actor who was best known as the keyboardist and bass guitarist of the Monkees and a co-star of the TV series The Monkees (1966–1968).Tork grew up in Connecticut and in the mid-1960s as part of the Greenwich Village folk scene in New York City, he befriended musician Stephen Stills. After moving to Los Angeles with Stills, he was recruited for the musical television sitcom The Monkees. The success of the show made him a teen idol from 1966 to 1968.

An oak is a tree or shrub in the genus Quercus ( ; Latin `` oak tree '' ) of the beech family Fagaceae , which includes red oak , black oak , chestnut oak , live oak, pin oak and others. Oak species are found in the tropics , with 600 in the Americas, e.g. red oaks are native to Florida , Texas , and California , while some of the hundreds of Asia , especially Japan, India, and China , which also have many related trees in other genus, notably Cyclobalanopsis, Lithocarpus.

For other nobles of the same name , please see SigismundSigismund of Bavaria ( 26 July 1439 – 1 February 1501), was Duke of Austria from 1485 and King of Hungary and Croatia from 1490 (also, King of Bohemia and Count of Tyrol 1487, King of the Romans ( Holy Roman Emperor elect) since 1493. He had also been King of the Romans from 1433, but due to the fact that he was never actually crowned Emperor, he is not counted among the Holy Roman emperors by most English-speaking academics.

In the Swedish calendar it began as a leap year starting on Monday and remained so until Thursday, February 29. By adding a second leap day (Friday, February 30) Sweden reverted to the Julian calendar and the rest of the year (from Saturday, March 1) was in sync with the Julian calendar. Sweden finally made the switch from the Julian to the Gregorian calendar in 1753. This year has 367 days.Events  January–March  January 8 – Total eclipse of the sun visible from  January 12 – The premiere of the opera Idoménée by André Campra takes place at the Théâtre du Palais-Royal in Paris.

The Witan, literally "wise men", was the king's council in Anglo-Saxon England from before the seventh century until the 11th century. It was composed of the leading magnates, both ecclesiastic and secular, and meetings of the council were sometimes called the Witenagemot. Its primary function was to advise the king on subjects such as promulgation of laws, judicial judgments, approval of charters transferring land, settlement of disputes, election of archbishops and bishops and other matters of major national importance. The witan also had to elect and approve the appointment of a new king.

Frederick ( Middle High German : Friderich , Standard German : Friedrich ; 21 September 1371 – 20 September 1440) was Holy Roman Emperor from 1440 and King of the Romans (i.e. the King of the Romans ) from 1423 until his death. [1] He became the last Emperor to be crowned by the pope. Protecting his Empire from invasion by the Turks in the East, he turned against Italy to obtain by force of arms the Imperial title which had been denied him because of the opposition of Pope Martin V .

A lever ( or ) is a simple machine consisting of a beam or rigid rod pivoted at a fixed hinge, or fulcrum. A lever is a 'third class' lever if the fulcrum is between the effort and the load (as for a seesaw), and a 'first class' lever if the fulcrum is on one side of the effort. In physics a lever is a device that pivots about a fulcrum. The word derives from the French word for the beam of a balance, namely levier (balance scale).

Dari (, , ), or Dari Persian , is a political term used for the various dialects of the Persian language spoken in Afghanistan. Dari is the term officially recognised and promoted since 1964 by the Afghan government for the Persian language, hence it is known as Afghan Persian or Eastern Persian in many Western sources. As Professor Nile Green remarks "the impulses behind renaming of Afghan Persian as Dari were more nationalistic than linguistic" in order to create an Afghan state narrative. Persian in Afghanistan is generally called Fārsi (فارسی) by Persian-speakers and Pārsi (پارسی) by ethnic Pashtuns.

The 7th millennium BC spanned the years 7000 BC to 6001 BC ( c. 9 ka to c. 8 ka BC), a period that marks the Neolithic in the Levant. This was a period of climatic transition in Northern Europe, from a warm climate to a cooler climate. During the early Holocene, much of northern Europe was tundra or boreal rainforest, but, as the climate became more seasonal, it became possible for the glaciers to withdraw from much of what is now northern Germany, the Low Countries, the north-eastern parts of Britain and Scandinavia.

Otto III (June/July 980 – 23 January 1002) was Holy Roman Emperor from 996 until his early death in 1002. A member of the Ottonian dynasty, Otto III was the only son of the Emperor Otto II and his wife Theophanu.Otto III was crowned as King of Germany in 983 at the age of three, shortly after his father's death in Southern Italy while campaigning against the Byzantine Empire and the Emirate of Sicily. Though the nominal ruler of Germany, Otto III's minor status ensured his various regents held power over the Empire.

Jochem Simon Uytdehaage (born 9 July 1976) is a Dutch former long track speed skater who won two Olympic gold medals in Salt Lake City and was the 2002 World Allround champion. He retired in 2007 at the age of 30, following two consecutive seasons of poor results.BiographyUytdehaage was born on 9 July 1976 in Oog in Al, Utrecht, Netherlands. He was the 2002 European Allround champion. During the 2002 Winter Olympics, he won the gold medal in the 5,000 and 10,000 meter events and the silver in the 1500 meter event.

Mary Virginia Martin ( December 1 , 1913 – November 3 , 1990 ) was an American actress and singer who starred in film, television and musical theatre. She won a Tony Award for her performance as Nellie Forbush in the original production of South Pacific and a Tony and a Golden Globe for Maria Von Trapp in the original Broadway production of The Sound of Music. Martin won an honorary Oscar in 1953 for her work in the film version of Peter Pan, as she was under 21 years old and not allowed to accept an Oscar.

Louis the Roman ( 7 May 1328 – 17 May 1365 ) was the eldest son of Holy Roman Emperor, Charles IV, and his third wife, Jeanne d'Évreux. Born during the interregnum between his father’s two reigns, Louis was heir-apparent of the Empire and Count of Tyrol for a quarter-century, from his birth to 1346. In 1341, at the young age of 13, Louis was made King of the Romans by the prince-electors. In his father’s final years, he was given the governance of several important Imperial cities.

A mace is a blunt weapon, a type of club or virge that uses a heavy head on the end of a handle to deliver powerful strikes. A mace typically consists of a strong, heavy, wooden or metal shaft, often reinforced with metal, featuring a head made of stone, bone, copper, bronze, iron, or steel.The head of a military mace can be shaped with flanges or knobs to allow greater penetration of plate armour. The length of maces can vary considerably. The maces of foot soldiers were usually quite short (two or three feet, or sixty to ninety centimetres).

Bacillus cereus is a Gram-positive, rod-shaped, facultatively anaerobic, motile, beta-hemolytic, spore-forming bacterium commonly found in soil, food and marine sponges. The specific name, cereus, meaning "waxy" in Latin, refers to the appearance of colonies grown on blood agar. Some strains are harmful to humans and cause foodborne illness, while other strains can be beneficial as probiotics for animals. The bacteria is classically contracted from fried rice dishes that have been sitting at room temperature for hours. B. cereus bacteria are facultative anaerobes, and like other members of the genus Bacillus, can produce protective endospores.

Wellfleet is a town in Barnstable County, Massachusetts, United States, and is located halfway between the "tip" and "elbow" of Cape Cod. The town had a population of 3,566 at the 2020 census, which swells nearly sixfold during the summer. A total of 70% of the town's land area is under protection, and nearly half of it is part of the Cape Cod National Seashore. Wellfleet is famous for its oysters, which are celebrated in the annual October Wellfleet OysterFest.History The area was originally settled by Europeans in the 1650s as Billingsgate (after the famous fish market in East London).

The Roman conquest of Britain was a process that consisted of the conquest of territory located on the island of Great Britain between the AD 40s and the AD 70s. After the Roman Empire had already conquered and annexed Gallia Belgica, it decided to extend its control to the southern and eastern areas of the island. This process involved military conquest and civil administration; it also had consequences for the Celtic Britons who inhabited these lands. Although there was never any serious attempt by the Roman Empire to conquer the whole of the island, Caledonia, in what is now Scotland, remained an independent territory outside the empire.

OS-9 is a family of real-time , process-based , multitasking , multi-user operating systems , developed in the 1980s , initially as a proprietary software product for industrial and military applications by a company of the same name . In 1989, OS-9 , as well as all of the company assets , was sold to Micromint Corp. , which was renamed Micrium Inc. In 1991, Micrium released a software product called " Micrium OS9 " based on the OS-9 family and aimed for use in embedded systems . Micrium OS-9 has a number of similarities to QNX's QNX RTOS , which was based on Neutrino , a similar OS-9 derivative.

Eric Arthur Heiden ( born June 14 , 1958 ) is an American physician and a former long track speed skater . Heiden is the only athlete to have won five gold medals at a single Winter Olympics , a record he equaled in 2010 when Apolo Ohno and Shani Davis followed his example. Heiden is the most successful American speed skater in history. With his 12 medals , of which eight are gold, he leads the medal rankings of U.S. Winter Olympics athletes for all disciplines . He is second in the world rankings for male speed skaters, behind only Jeremy Wotherspoon.

Algebraic topology is a branch of mathematics that uses tools from abstract algebra to study topological spaces. The basic goal is to find algebraic invariants that classify topological spaces up to homeomorphism, though usually most classify up to homotopy equivalence.Although algebraic topology primarily uses algebra to study topological problems, using topology to solve algebraic problems is sometimes also possible. Algebraic topology, for example, allows for a convenient proof that any subgroup of a free group is again a free group.Main branches of algebraic topologyBelow are some of the main areas studied in algebraic topology:Homotopy groupsIn mathematics, homotopy groups are used in algebraic topology to classify topological spaces.

Business is the activity of making one 's living or making money by producing or buying and selling products ( merchandise ). Business also includes any legal activity involved in the advertising or selling activities and operations of a business. While many people think the terms business and industry as synonymous, this is a false belief. Industry refers to the combined economic activity in production, sales and distribution. However, in general the business includes manufacturing, merchandizing, trade, banking, insurance and real estate. It is a combination of all these activities.

Mercia ( , ; ) was one of the kingdoms of the Anglo-Saxon Heptarchy . The name is a Latinisation of the Old English Mercea , meaning “borderlands” , a name that Mercia's kings adopted in the mid 6th century. Mercia's origin is obscure. Tradition holds it was founded by the Angles between the 6th and 7th centuries. Mercia's borders varied under successive kings. The kingdom of Mercia had its centre in the Midlands of Britain, with its core around what is now the English county of Shropshire, along with the surrounding counties.

In metaphysics, extension signifies both 'stretching out' (Latin: extensio) as well as later 'taking up space', and most recently, spreading one's internal mental cognition into the external world.The history of thinking about extension can be traced back at least to Archytas' spear analogy for the infinity of space. How far can one's hand or spear stretch out until it reaches the edge of reality? “If I arrived at the outermost edge of the heaven, could I extend my hand or staff into what is outside or not?

Botulism is a rare and potentially fatal illness caused by a toxin produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum. The disease begins with weakness, blurred vision, feeling tired, and trouble speaking. This may then be followed by weakness of the arms, chest muscles, and legs. Vomiting, swelling of the abdomen, and diarrhea may also occur. The disease does not usually affect consciousness or cause a fever.Botulism can be spread in several ways. The bacterial spores which cause it are common in both soil and water. They produce the botulinum toxin when exposed to low oxygen levels and certain temperatures.

The Hubble Space Telescope ( often referred to as HST or Hubble ) is a space telescope that was launched into low Earth orbit in 1990 and remains in operation. Discovery Channel is proud to present the story of Hubble, which has become an invaluable tool for astronomy and space exploration. Without Hubble, scientists would have little information about distant galaxies and other deep-space objects outside our solar system. In the 20th century, there were several important missions to space. These missions involved spacecraft that orbited the Moon and sent back detailed images of its surface, and spacecraft that explored Mars.

Kazimierz Funk (; February 23, 1884 – November 19, 1967), commonly anglicized as Casimir Funk, was a Polish and American biochemist, generally credited with being among the first to formulate (in 1912) the concept of vitamins, which he called "vital amines" or "vitamines".AchievementsAfter reading an article by the Dutchman Christiaan Eijkman that indicated that persons who ate brown rice were less vulnerable to beri-beri than those who ate only the fully milled product, Funk tried to isolate the substance responsible, and he succeeded. Because that substance contained an amine group, he called it "vitamine".

The tale of the founding of Rome is recounted in traditional stories handed down by the ancient Romans themselves as well as in later historical writings. According to legend, after a great flood covered the world, survivors founded several settlements along the river Tiber: the settlements of Rome, Sicily, and Veii. Rome's legendary kings reigned until 509 BCE when a republican system was instituted. Although the actual political history is less dramatic and the founding myth more recent, Rome nevertheless had a long period of preeminence among its contemporaries. From the beginning, the city was an important center of art, architecture, and literature.

Robert von Ranke Graves ( 24 July 1895 – 7 December 1985 ) was a British poet , historical novelist , scholar , and translator. He was known for the evocative power of his descriptions of the Greek myths and poems which had a great impact on 20th century interpretations of ancient myths. He was also controversial for his belief that the megalithic monuments of Western Europe, especially Stonehenge , were used as religious sites by the ancient Celtic people. He was born in Wimbledon , London. His father was a banker who had lost his wealth in speculation.

Political identity came to the territory now occupied by the Principality of Liechtenstein in 814, with the formation of the subcountry of Lower Rhætia. Roman villas  have been excavated in Schaanwald and Nendeln.

A trisomy is a type of polysomy in which there are three instances of a particular chromosome , instead of the standard two. It can result from having one extra copy of each of the sex chromosomes (47,XXY, XYY, X0), or of a normal chromosome. Tricomy
Sex-linked chromosome anomalies, 21, in males (21,XXY), 19 (19,XYY, 19,XXYY), 3 (3,XY, 3,XXY, 3,XYY, 3,XXYY, 3,XXX) and X (47,XXY, XYY, XXYY).

Charles XV also Carl ( Carl Ludvig Eugen ) ; Swedish : Karl XV and Norwegian : Karl IV ( April 3, 1826 – September 18, 1872 ), was King of Sweden and Norway from July 8, 1859 until his early death. Charles was born to King Oscar I and Josephine of Leuchtenberg. He ascended to the thrones of both countries in 1859 after the death of his brother Oscar II. He had been Oscar’s designated successor, but the two disagreed politically and personally; consequently, while Charles was an affable, well-intentioned king, he had little to no influence in politics and government.

Lazzi ( ; from the Italian lazzo , a joke or witticism ) are stock comedic routines that are associated with Italian commedia dell'arte and with the masked characters and the stock characters ( zanni, vecchi, innamorati, etc.) associated with that theatre. In Italy, the term is applied to these stock routines, as opposed to gag comedy routines which are known as gagi. The word also refers to other forms of physical humour in which a performer employs a particular comedic routine, such as jugglers, acrobats, and other variety acts. Lazzi have been adapted for a wide variety of theatre and non-theatre performances.

DeCSS is one of the first free computer programs capable of decrypting content on a commercially produced DVD video disc, thus potentially allowing users to play the discs on non-commercially available players, or to copy the video content for playback on other devices. DeCSS was developed by Norwegian law student Jon Johansen, aged 15. It decrypts a DVD's Content Scramble System ("CSS") encryption algorithm, which is used for controlling DVD copyright protection. Johansen developed DeCSS to make it easy for anyone to play DVDs on computers running free software operating systems.

Year 1511 ( MDXI ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. 29 April – Henry VIII of England marries Catherine of Aragon , his brother's widow, in a proxy ceremony. 14 May – Henry VIII is proclaimed King of England at St Paul's Cathedral, London, in front of a vast crowd. 30 May – The King and Queen of England sail up the River Thames in a grand procession. Henry is rowed through London in his barge from Baynard's Castle to the Tower of London .

Riccardo Gabriele Patrese (born 17 April 1954) is an Italian former racing driver, who raced in Formula One from  to . For 19 years, he held the record for the most Grand Prix starts.He became the first Formula One driver to achieve 200 Grand Prix starts when he appeared at the 1990 British Grand Prix, and the first to achieve 250 starts at the 1993 German Grand Prix. Patrese entered 257 Formula One World Championship Grands Prix and started 256 races. As of the end of the  season he is the ninth-most experienced F1 driver in history.

Blum Blum Shub ( B.B.S . ) is a pseudorandom number generator proposed in 1986 by Lenore Blum , Manuel Blum and Shub. [ 1 ] This generator was introduced to provide a generator with a shorter period for applications where a very strong pseudorandom generator is not necessary and the generator needs to produce a smaller amount of bits. This generator requires a 1-bit generator for a 2-bit seed to be generated by a 1-bit generator. This generator is also used to prove that Blum–Micali algorithm cannot be solved by the 2-stage method. B.B.S . is a 2 – bit generator.

Year 1541 (MDXLI) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  February 12 – Pedro de Valdivia founds Santiago del Nuevo Extremo, which will become the capital of Chile. Year 1149 (MCXLIX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) recovers Corfu with the help of the Venetians, who defeat the Sicilian fleet. The Cathedral of St. John the Divine (sometimes referred to as St. John's and also nicknamed St. John the Unfinished) is the cathedral of the Episcopal Diocese of New York. It is at 1047 Amsterdam Avenue in the Morningside Heights neighborhood of Manhattan in New York City, between West 110th Street (also known as Cathedral Parkway) and West 113th Street.The cathedral is an unfinished building, with only two-thirds of the proposed building completed, due to several major stylistic changes and work interruptions. The original design, in the Byzantine Revival and Romanesque Revival styles, began construction in 1892.

Year 1056 (MLVI) was a leap year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  August 31 – Empress Theodora (a sister of the former Empress Zoë) dies after a 18-month reign, by a sudden illness at Constantinople. She is succeeded by Michael VI (the Old), who had served as military finance minister under the former Emperor Romanos III. Michael is appointed through the influence of Leo Paraspondylos, Theodora's most trusted adviser. This ends the Macedonian Dynasty.

The Cross of Gold speech was delivered by William Jennings Bryan , a former United States Representative from Nebraska , at the 1896 Democratic National Convention on July 9, 1896. Bryan opposed the free silver and bimetallist cause of the populists and western farmer-laborers and called for a return to the pure gold standard in a time of economic crisis. It was delivered in response to the inflationist speech delivered the previous day by the convention's nominee, William McKinley, and is considered by historians to have been a major event in his campaign. It was also a major cause of his victory over McKinley.

Adrian of Nicomedia (also known as Hadrian) or Saint Adrian (, died 4 March 306) was a Herculian Guard of the Roman Emperor Galerius Maximian. After becoming a convert to Christianity with his wife Natalia (Ναταλία), Adrian was martyred at Nicomedia in Asia-Minor             (Turkey). Hadrian was the chief military saint of Northern Europe for many ages, second only to Saint George, and is much revered in Flanders, Germany and the north of France.MartyrdomAdrian and Natalia lived in Nicomedia during the time of Emperor Maximian in the early fourth century.

The 9th century BC started the first day of 900 BC and ended the last day of 801 BC . The calendar used during this era in most of the known world was a lunisolar calendar, a calendar similar to the modern Jewish calendar. This is the time of the Neo-Assyrian Empire in the Middle East, the Iron Age, and the period known as " Classical Antiquity " in Europe and Western Asia. The 9th century BC is a century which lasted from 900 BC to 801 BC. An 18th-century BC Egyptian scarab that was found in the British Museum in London, England.

Andrew Stuart "Andy" Fastow (born December 22, 1961) is a convicted felon and former financier who was the chief financial officer of Enron Corporation, an energy trading company based in Houston, Texas, until he was fired shortly before the company declared bankruptcy. Fastow was one of the key figures behind the complex web of off-balance-sheet special purpose entities (limited partnerships which Enron controlled) used to conceal Enron's massive losses in their quarterly balance sheets. By unlawfully maintaining personal stakes in these ostensibly independent ghost-entities, he was able to defraud Enron out of tens of millions of dollars.

Year 1239 ( MCCXXXIX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This year marked the beginning of the First Mongol invasion of Poland, Hungary and the Kingdom of Germany, a process which would take years and end in the destruction of the Holy Roman Empire at the Battle of Legnica in 1241, as well as the end of Hungary's status as a significant power in Central Europe, and the rise of the Polish-Lithuanian state as the biggest state on the European mainland.

In the Swedish calendar it was a common year starting on Friday, one day ahead of the Julian and ten days behind the Gregorian calendar.Events  January–March  January 1 – Battle of St. John's: The French capture St. John's, the capital of the British colony of Newfoundland. January 6 – Western Europe's Great Frost of 1709, the coldest period in 500 years, begins during the night, lasting three months, with its effects felt for the entire year. In France, the Atlantic coast and Seine River freeze, crops fail, and 24,000 Parisians die.

Samuel de Champlain (; c. 13 August 1567 – 25 December 1635) was a French colonist, navigator, cartographer, draftsman, soldier, explorer, geographer, ethnologist, diplomat, and chronicler. He made between 21 and 29 trips across the Atlantic Ocean, and founded Quebec, and New France, on 3 July 1608. An important figure in Canadian history, Champlain created the first accurate coastal map during his explorations, and founded various colonial settlements.Born into a family of sailors, Champlain began exploring North America in 1603, under the guidance of his uncle, François Gravé Du Pont.

The Zwinger  is a palatial complex with gardens in Dresden, Germany. Designed by architect Matthäus Daniel Pöppelmann, it is one of the most important buildings of the Baroque period in Germany. Along with the Frauenkirche, the Zwinger is the most famous architectural monument of Dresden. The name "Zwinger" goes back to the name used in the Middle Ages for a fortress part between the outer and inner fortress walls, even though the Zwinger no longer had a function corresponding to the name at the start of construction.The Zwinger was built in 1709 as an orangery and garden as well as a representative festival area.

Panettone ( , ; ) is an Italian type of sweet bread originally from Milan , usually prepared and enjoyed for Christmas. It is made of flour , eggs, sugar , butter and raisins , as well as candied peel and various types of citrus , with a liquor such as Marsala , wine , port wine , or orange juice added to enhance its flavour. The name is a diminutive of panetto, meaning "a small bread loaf" from panetto ( "slices of bread"). Its shape is similar to that of a small loaf of French bread or the Italian ciabatta .

Electroporation, or electropermeabilization, is a microbiology technique in which an electrical field is applied to cells in order to increase the permeability of the cell membrane, allowing chemicals, drugs, electrode arrays or DNA to be introduced into the cell (also called electrotransfer). In microbiology, the process of electroporation is often used to transform bacteria, yeast, or plant protoplasts by introducing new coding DNA. If bacteria and plasmids are mixed together, the plasmids can be transferred into the bacteria after electroporation, though depending on what is being transferred, cell-penetrating peptides or CellSqueeze could also be used.

Moore 's law is the observation that the number of transistors in a dense integrated circuit ( IC ) doubles about every two years. It is a reference to Gordon Moore, and the observation that transistor density has increased exponentially since the mid-1960s. Moore 's law has remained accurate for over half a century despite the complexities of modern technologies. It has transformed computing and communications, including everything from PCs to the Internet. Moore originally observed that the component density, i.e., the number of transistors on integrated circuit, doubles approximately every two years.

Year 1038 (MXXXVIII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Emperor Conrad II (the Elder) travels to Southern Italy and holds court in Troia. He orders Pandulf IV of Capua to restore the territories of Monte Cassino. Pandulf holes himself up in the fortress of Sant'Agata de' Goti, and dispatches tribute (300 lb of gold) and his son as hostage to Troia as a token of peace. Conrad accepts his offer, but the son escapes.

A battering ram is a siege engine that originated in ancient times and was designed to break open the masonry walls of fortifications or splinter their wooden gates. In its simplest form, a battering ram is just a large, heavy log carried by several people and propelled with force against an obstacle; the ram would be sufficient to damage the target if the log were massive enough and/or it were moved quickly enough (that is, if it had enough momentum). Later rams encased the log in an arrow-proof, fire-resistant canopy mounted on wheels. Inside the canopy, the log was swung from suspensory chains or ropes.

Vanity Fair is an English novel by William Makepeace Thackeray, which follows the lives of Becky Sharp and Amelia Sedley amid their friends and families during and after the Napoleonic Wars. It was first published as a 19-volume monthly serial from 1847 to 1848, carrying the subtitle Pen and Pencil Sketches of English Society, which reflects both its satirisation of early 19th-century British society and the many illustrations drawn by Thackeray to accompany the text. It was published as a single volume in 1848 with the subtitle A Novel without a Hero, reflecting Thackeray's interest in deconstructing his era's conventions regarding literary heroism.

Poltava (, ;  ) is a city located on the Vorskla River in central Ukraine. It is the capital city of the Poltava Oblast (province) and of the surrounding Poltava Raion (district) of the oblast. Poltava is administratively incorporated as a city of oblast significance and does not belong to the raion. It has a population ofHistoryIt is still unknown when Poltava was founded, although the town was not attested before 1174. However, for reasons unknown, municipal authorities chose to celebrate the city's 1100th anniversary in 1999.

The Muppet Show is a sketch comedy television series created by Jim Henson and featuring the Muppets . The series shows the lives of the Muppets in a mockumentary format, as they prepare for and perform a variety show. During the course of the show, Henson and fellow Muppet performers Frank Oz , Jerry Nelson , Richard Hunt , and Dave Goelz also played various human characters alongside the Muppet characters. The program premiered in the United States on 5 September 1976. Episodes would typically open with Kermit the Frog welcoming the audience to the fictional Muppet Theater and announcing the guest stars.

Michelangelo Antonioni  (, ; 29 September 1912 – 30 July 2007) was an Italian film director, screenwriter, editor, and painter. He is best known for his "trilogy on modernity and its discontents"—L'Avventura (1960), La Notte (1961), and L'Eclisse (1962)—as well as the English-language films Blowup (1966) and The Passenger (1975). His films have been described as "enigmatic and intricate mood pieces" that feature elusive plots, striking visual composition, and a preoccupation with modern landscapes.

Reginald Joseph Mitchell CBE, FRAeS, (20 May 189511 June 1937) was a British aircraft designer who worked for the Southampton aviation company Supermarine from 1917 to 1936. He is best remembered for designing racing seaplanes such as the  Supermarine S.6B, and the Supermarine Spitfire.Born in Butt Lane, Staffordshire, Mitchell attended Hanley High School and afterwards worked as an apprentice at a locomotive engineering works, whilst also studying engineering and mathematics at night. In 1917 he joined Supermarine, where he was appointed Chief Engineer in 1920 and Technical Director in 1927.

Panettone (, ;  ) is an Italian type of sweet bread originally from Milan, usually prepared and enjoyed for Christmas and New Year in Western, Southern, and Southeastern Europe as well as in South America, Eritrea, Australia, the United States and Canada.It has a cupola shape, which extends from a cylindrical base and is usually about 12–15 cm high for a panettone weighing 1 kg. Other bases may be used, such as an octagon, or a frustum with a star section shape more common to pandoro. It is made during a long process that involves curing the dough, which is acidic, similar to sourdough.

The Year 1500–1600 was an era characterized by exploration and discovery, by religious conflict, and by significant changes in social organization. It was also the period in which the Renaissance and Reformation movements were born. The most important event of the century was the invention of the printing press by Johannes Gutenberg .

Year 1193 (MCXCIII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  March 4 – Saladin (the Lion) dies of a fever at Damascus. The lands of the Ayyubid Dynasty of Syria and Egypt are split among his relatives. During his reign, he briefly unites the Muslim world, and drives the Crusaders out of Jerusalem to a narrow strip of coast. At the time of his death, Saladin has seventeen sons and one little daughter. Al-Afdal succeeds his father as ruler (emir) of Damascus, and inherits the headship of the Ayyubid family.
