Dissociative identity disorder ( DID ) , previously known as multiple personality disorder ( MPD ) , is a mental health condition in which two or more distinct identities, or personalities, are present in an individual. Dissociative identity disorder has been described since at least the 16th Century, but it has only recently been officially recognised as a distinct disorder. It is believed that the number of individuals affected by DID is less than one in 1,000, and that there is no evidence of its prevalence or incidence across cultures. DID is also sometimes called ‘split personality disorder’.

Observations show that the expansion of the universe is accelerating, such that the velocity at which a distant galaxy recedes from the observer is continuously increasing with time.The accelerated expansion was discovered during 1998, by two independent projects, the Supernova Cosmology Project and the High-Z Supernova Search Team, which both used distant type Ia supernovae to measure the acceleration. The idea was that as type Ia supernovae have almost the same intrinsic brightness (a standard candle), and since objects that are further away appear dimmer, we can use the observed brightness of these supernovae to measure the distance to them.

OS-9 is a family of real-time, process-based, multitasking, multi-user operating systems, developed in the 1980s, originally by Microware Systems Corporation for the Motorola 6809 microprocessor. It was purchased by Radisys Corp in 2001, and was purchased again in 2013 by its current owner Microware LP.The OS-9 family was popular for general-purpose computing and remains in use in commercial embedded systems and amongst hobbyists. Today, OS-9 is a product name used by both a Motorola 68000-series machine language OS and a portable (PowerPC, x86, ARM, MIPS, SH4, etc.)

Mai Elisabeth Zetterling (; 24 May 1925 – 17 March 1994) was a Swedish actress, novelist and film director.Early lifeZetterling was born in Västerås, Sweden to a working class family. She started her career as an actress at the age of 17 at Dramaten, the Swedish national theatre, appearing in war-era films.CareerZetterling appeared in film and television productions spanning six decades from the 1940s to the 1990s. Her breakthrough came in the 1944 film Torment written by Ingmar Bergman, in which she played a controversial role as a tormented shopgirl.

The Tandy 1000 is the first in a line of IBM PC compatible home computer systems produced by the Tandy Corporation for sale in its Radio Shack and Radio Shack Computer Center chains of stores.OverviewIn December 1983, an executive with Tandy Corporation, maker of TRS-80 computers, said about the new IBM PCjr: "I'm sure a lot of people will be coming out with PCjr look-alikes. The market is big". While preparing the Tandy 2000—the company's first MS-DOS computer—for release in November 1983, Tandy began designing the Tandy 1000, code named "August".

Perpignan ( , , ; ; ; ) is the prefecture of the Pyrénées-Orientales department ( known as Northern Catalonia in English, Northern Catalonia in Catalan, Cerdanya in Spanish, Cerdanyès in Catalan and Occitan). It is the capital of the region called Roussillon in French. Perpignan was the capital of the former province and region of Roussillon, and the presidency of North-East Catalonia until 2015. Perpignan is the fourth largest city in Catalonia. It lies between the Mediterranean Sea (Lake of Canet-Saint Nazaire) to the east, and the Pyrenees to the north and northwest, and it is 50 kilometres south of the France-Spain border.

In computer programming , a postcondition is a condition or predicate that must always be true just after the execution of an algorithm, a procedure , a routine , or a function returns from its execution. In object-oriented design , postconditions are associated with methods , as they are in design by contract . The postcondition is the statement that describes what changes have happened inside the algorithm since its execution has started. The postcondition is the opposite of precondition . For the function, precondition is the condition before the function is called and postcondition is the condition after it has returned.

The earliest arrival of people in the islands now known as The Bahamas was in the first millennium AD . However, it wasn’t until around 1200 AD that people began to settle the Bahamas as we know them today, as a group known as the Lucayan were the first to make the islands inhabitable. The Lucayans lived mainly along the banks of the many rivers that criss-crossed the islands and it is through the many artifacts left by the group that archeologists have pieced together their way of life. The Bahamas were discovered by European explorers around 1492 and were settled shortly after in 1647 by England.

arXiv ( pronounced `` archive '' —the X represents the Greek letter chi [ χ ] ) is an open-access online repository of theses, preprints and other scientific papers. Papers are uploaded by authors and then distributed via the internet. It is also known as "e-print archive". It was initially set up in 1991 at Los Alamos National Laboratory as means for scientists to share technical reports. Now, over 1000 people, institutions and companies have contributed. The name is pronounced "archive" as "archive" spelled with a Greek letter chi rather than X.

Year 1344 ( MCCCXLIV ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. 22 March – Battle of Sluys: English fleet destroys French fleet in a naval battle. 12 June – Battle of Auberoche: English besieging army is defeated by a French relief force. 13 July – The Order of the Garter founded by King Edward III of England at Windsor. 18 September – Pope Clement VI sends a letter of peace to the leaders of the Kingdom of Scotland. 9 October – The University of Prague receives a charter from Emperor Charles IV.

In probability theory , the central limit theorem ( CLT ) establishes that , in many situations , when independent random variables are averaged, their properly normalized sum tends to a normal distribution , regardless of the actual distribution from which they were drawn and of the initial magnitude of their variations. The theorem has many applications in various fields of mathematics , statistics , engineering , and science . The theorem was first published in 1835 by Augustin Louis Cauchy . In his work, Cauchy showed that the sampling distribution of the mean is approximately normal , provided that the sample size is large enough .

The 7th millennium BC spanned the years 7000 BC to 6001 BC (c. 9 ka to c. 8 ka). It is impossible to precisely date events around this millennium, and all dates mentioned here are estimates mostly based on geological and anthropological analysis. Towards the end of this millennium, the islands of Great Britain and Ireland were severed from continental Europe by rising seawater.CommunitiesPopulationNeolithic culture and technology were established in the Near East by 7000 BC and there is increasing evidence through the millennium of its spread or introduction to Europe and the Far East.

In mathematics, open sets are a generalization of  open intervals in the real line. In a metric space—that is, when a distance function is defined—open sets are the sets that, with every point , contain all points that are sufficiently near to  (that is, all points whose distance to  is less than some value depending on ).More generally, one defines open sets as the members of a given collection of subsets of a given set, a collection that has the property of containing every union of its members, every finite intersection of its members, the empty set, and the whole set itself.

Mariner 3 ( together with Mariner 4 known as Mariner-Mars 1964 ) was one of two identical deep-space probes designed by NASA to investigate Mars as part of the Mars Program. The launch of the Mariner probes was originally planned as a joint Soviet-American mission, but the Soviet space agency, the Russian Academy of Sciences, was forced to withdraw from the effort when the United States placed the launch of a Delta II rocket, which had already been bought, under restriction because of the Soviet space program. In addition to a camera, the Mariner space probe carried various instruments for studying the atmosphere and soil.

Spiro Theodore Agnew (November 9, 1918 – September 17, 1996) was the 39th vice president of the United States, serving from 1969 until his resignation in 1973. He is the second vice president to resign the position, the other being John C. Calhoun in 1832. Agnew was born in Baltimore to a Greek immigrant father and an American mother. He attended Johns Hopkins University and graduated from the University of Baltimore School of Law. He worked as an aide to U.S. Representative James Devereux before he was appointed to the Baltimore County Board of Zoning Appeals in 1957.

Year 1051 ( MLI ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar . 1051 (or 1051 BC) is a year that occurred in the 11th century (1st millennium). In Europe, it is the year 10th century of the Christian era and Anno Domini 1051 . In astronomy , a common year starting on Tuesday (dominical letter D) of the Julian calendar was the first year to have a Monday in April. This year had 12 months and 304 days. It was part of an 80-year cycle.

The hobby of collecting includes seeking, locating, acquiring, organizing, cataloging, displaying, storing, and maintaining items that are of interest to an individual collector. Collections differ in a wide variety of respects, most obviously in the nature and scope of the objects contained, but also in purpose, presentation, and so forth. The range of possible subjects for a collection is practically unlimited, and collectors have realised a vast number of these possibilities in practice, although some are much more popular than others.In collections of manufactured items, the objects may be antique or simply collectable.

Sigismund (26 October 1427 – 4 March 1496), a member of the House of Habsburg, was Duke of Austria from 1439 (elevated to Archduke in 1477) until his death. As a scion of the Habsburg Leopoldian line, he ruled over Further Austria and the County of Tyrol from 1446 until his resignation in 1490.BiographySigismund (or Siegmund, sometimes also spelled Sigmund) was born at the Tyrolean court in Innsbruck; his parents were the Further Austrian duke Frederick IV of Austria and his second wife , a daughter of the Welf duke Frederick I of Brunswick-Lüneburg.

J. Robert Oppenheimer (; April 22, 1904 – February 18, 1967) was an American theoretical physicist who was professor of physics at the University of California, Berkeley. Oppenheimer was the wartime head of the Los Alamos Laboratory and is among those who are credited with being the "father of the atomic bomb" for their role in the Manhattan Project – the World War II undertaking that developed the first nuclear weapons. Oppenheimer was among those who observed the Trinity test in New Mexico, where the first atomic bomb was successfully detonated on July 16, 1945.

is the Latin name under which the "Lamb of God" is honoured within the Catholic Mass and other Christian liturgies descending from the Latin liturgical tradition. Year 1132 (MCXXXII) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  Summer – Imad al-Din Zengi, Seljuk governor (atabeg) of Aleppo and Mosul, marches on Baghdad (the capital of the Abbasid Caliphate) to add it to his dominions. He is defeated by the forces of Caliph Al-Mustarshid near Tikrit (modern Iraq). Zengi flees and escapes with help of Tikrit's governor Najm ad-Din Ayyub (the father of Saladin) who conveys him across the River Tigris.

Howard Kingsbury Smith (May 12, 1914 – February 15, 2002) was an American journalist, radio reporter, television anchorman, political commentator, and film actor. He was one of the original members of the team of war correspondents known as the Murrow Boys.Early life and educationEarly career and CBS yearsWorld War IIUpon graduating, Smith worked for the New Orleans Item, with United Press in London, and with The New York Times. In January 1940, Smith was sent to Berlin, where he joined the Columbia Broadcasting System under Edward R. Murrow.

Major League Baseball ( MLB ) is a professional baseball organization and the oldest major professional sports league in the United States and Canada, dating to the 19th century. NCAA Men's Basketball Tournament - NCAA Division I Football Championship - National Football League (NFL)

Vapor pressure (or vapour pressure in English-speaking counties other than the US; see spelling differences) or equilibrium vapor pressure is defined as the pressure exerted by a vapor in thermodynamic equilibrium with its condensed phases (solid or liquid) at a given temperature in a closed system. The equilibrium vapor pressure is an indication of a liquid's evaporation rate. It relates to the tendency of particles to escape from the liquid (or a solid). A substance with a high vapor pressure at normal temperatures is often referred to as volatile. The pressure exhibited by vapor present above a liquid surface is known as vapor pressure.

Year 1355 (MCCCLV) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January 6 – Charles IV of Bohemia is crowned with the Iron Crown of Lombardy as King of Italy in Milan. January 7 – King Alphonso IV of Portugal sends three men who kill Inês de Castro, beloved of his son Peter, who revolts and incites a civil war. February 10 – St Scholastica Day riot in Oxford, England, breaks out, leaving 63 scholars and perhaps 30 locals dead in two days.

A sifaka is a lemur of the genus Propithecus from the family Indriidae within the order Primates . The name sifaka means "sifaka-type animal" in Malagasy , referring to a type of Malagasy dance. There are five species in this genus, which are collectively called "sportive lemurs" or "dancing lemurs." They are very agile animals, and can bound from one tree to another. Their long toes allow them to grasp the branches they need to move on, but this also allows them to be adept at walking on the ground.

Events  January–March  January 5 – The Brandenburger—African Company, of the German state of Brandenburg, signs a greaty with representatives of the Ahanta tribe in what is now Ghana to establish the fort and settlement of Groß Friedrichsburg in honor of Frederick William, Elector of Brandenburg. The location is later renamed Princes Town, also called Pokesu. January 6 – The tragic opera Phaëton, written by Jean-Baptiste Lully and Philippe Quinault, is premiered at the Palace of Versailles. January 27 – Gove's Rebellion breaks out in the Province of New Hampshire in North America as a revolt against the Royal Governor, Edward Cranfield.

Dari ( , , ) , or Dari Persian , is a political term used for the various dialects of modern Persian spoken primarily in Afganistan and Uzbekistan. The dialects are grouped into Northern Dari ( also called Afghan Persian), Western Dari , and Eastern Dari . Northern Dari (also known as Farsi ) is spoken by most Afganis in the northern regions of Afganistan and by the majority of Afghanistan's urban population . Western Dari (also known as Herati Persian) is spoken by Afganis living in the western region around Herat , as well as by the Hazara , and is also known as Dari-e-Mazari (from Mazar-e-Sharif ) .

It is considered by the Catholic Church to be the last of the seven years of tribulation before the Apocalypse predicted in the Book of Revelation, and is the year in which Pope Urban II preached the First Crusade. Year 1186 ( MCLXXXVI ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. 1186 is a number that equals 1186, in which the base-10 digits add to themselves. It is the first year to have this property. It is also the first year that this property is possessed by only one year. In the Julian calendar, the year was known as the 1388th year, with the Dominical letter being A. The number 1186 is divisible by the number 13 ( the sum of its digits ).

Events January–June January 14 – Portuguese Restoration War – Battle of the Lines of Elvas : The Portuguese beat the Spanish. January 18 – First Battle of Aland – Swedish forces invade the Aland Islands. March 8 – In the Battle of Sasbach, Imperial French army defeats the army of the rebel Elector of Bavaria. April 6 – In the Battle of Nördlingen, Sweden defeats an Imperial army. April 11 – The Royal Netherlands Marine Corps, the first regular marine unit in the Dutch Army, is founded. Nature versus nurture is a long-standing debate in biology about the balance between two competing factors which determine fate : the nature of genetic heredity and the influence of environmental factors on development. Traditionally the focus has often been on the degree to which human behaviour is due to genetic or environmental influences, but it can also take the form of the role of social factors within genetically identical populations. The nature versus nurture debate is an on-going discussion in the philosophy of biology. Aspects of human development can be seen as a mixture of inherited and environmental influences.

Year 1027 (MXXVII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  March 26 – Pope John XIX crowns Conrad II ("the Elder") and his wife Gisela of Swabia as Holy Roman Emperor and Empress, respectively, in Old St. Peter's Basilica in Rome. Cnut the Great, King of Denmark and England, attends the coronation, proving his position as sole ruler of the Danish North Sea Empire. May 14 – King Robert II of France ("the Pious") sues for peace with his sons.

Short-track speed skating is a form of competitive ice speed skating . In competitions , multiple skaters ( typically between four and six ) skate on an oval ice track with a circumference of 111.12m. This form of speed skating is sometimes confused with long-track speed skating because both use ice and ice skates , but the long track is much longer than the oval. The sport is an Olympic discipline, with the men's 1500 m and mass start races held in the Winter Olympic Games . World Championships have been held annually since 1976.

A battering ram is a siege engine that originated in ancient times and was designed to break open the masonry gates and fortifications of walled cities and castles. The device has been popularized in modern culture as the ram used by the 10th century Vikings to raid English settlements, although it is doubtful that the Vikings used this tool in actual warfare. The ram itself is a hard, heavy club with a pointed metal head attached to a heavy wooden pole that can be swung at a target in order to damage it or destroy it entirely. There are two types of battering ram, the beam and the trunnel.

Hawaii Five-O is an American police procedural drama series produced by CBS Productions and created by Leonard Freeman . Set in Hawaii , the executive producers are Leonard Freeman , Alex Kurtzman, Roberto Orci, Peter Lenkov, K/O Paper Products , Bruce Feiler ,Todd Horn ,Matt Pyken and Gary Fleder . On May 19, 2010, CBS announced that it had picked up the pilot to series. The pilot was filmed in March 2010. The series is a re-imagining of the original 1968–80 series, which followed Steve McGarrett , the head of an elite state police unit investigating organized crime on the island of Oahu , Hawaii.

The picometre (international spelling as used by the International Bureau of Weights and Measures; SI symbol: pm) or picometer (American spelling) is a unit of length in the metric system, equal to , or one trillionth  of a metre, which is the SI base unit of length.The picometre is one thousandth of a nanometre ( nm), one millionth of a micrometre (also known as a micron), one billionth of a millimetre, and one trillionth of a metre. The symbol μμ was once used for it.

Year 1165 (MCLXV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) makes an alliance with Venice against Emperor Frederick I (Barbarossa), who takes an oath at the Diet of Würzburg to support Antipope Paschal III against Pope Alexander III. Andronikos Komnenos, a cousin of Manuel I, escapes from prison at Constantinople. After passing through many dangers, he reaches Kiev and seeks refuge at the court of Prince Yaroslav Osmomysl.

The National Botanic Gardens ( Irish : Garraithe Náisiúnta na Lus ) is a botanical garden in Glasnevin , 5 km north of Dublin , Ireland. It is one of Ireland’s premier tourist attractions , with over 125,000 visitors a year. The garden is located on 197 acres in north Dublin. Its main gate on Nassau Street leads on to the Botanic Avenue, which continues into the grounds past the administrative building, ending at the Palm House. Other important buildings in the grounds are the Glasshouses, and the Plant Science Centre.

Tequila  is a distilled beverage made from the blue agave plant, primarily in the area surrounding the city of Tequila  northwest of Guadalajara, and in the Jaliscan Highlands (Los Altos de Jalisco) of the central western Mexican state of Jalisco.The red volcanic soils in the region of Tequila are well suited for growing the blue agave, and more than 300 million of the plants are harvested there each year. Agave grows differently depending on the region. Blue agaves grown in the highlands Los Altos region are larger and sweeter in aroma and taste. Agaves harvested in the valley region have a more herbaceous fragrance and flavor.

A Roman villa was typically a farmhouse or country house built in the Roman Republic and the Roman Empire , from roughly the 3 rd century BC to the occupation of southern and western Britain by the Romans in about AD 400/450. While rich citizens, especially of the provinces, often had villas, there were also thousands of smaller villas owned by the upper middle class and ordinary equestrian class, who would become extremely wealthy for the time by making a single shipment of grain to Rome. Villas also exist in parts of the Roman world outside of Italy, such as the Roman provinces of Gaul, Spain and North Africa.

Sigismund of Luxembourg ( 15 February 1368 – 9 December 1437 ) was a monarch who reigned as king of Hungary, Croatia and Bohemia. He was born to Charles IV, Holy Roman Emperor and queen Elizabeth, who was daughter of Peter I, Duke of Bourbon. His mother's cousin King Charles V of France appointed him Arch-Chamberlain of France. In 1433 he also became Elector of Brandenburg. He was the founder of a dynasty, the Luxembourg-Luxemburg dynasty that ruled the Kingdom of Hungary and several other countries. His father was King Charles IV and his mother Queen Elizabeth.

Black's Law Dictionary is the most widely used law dictionary in the United States. Henry Campbell Black (1860–1927) was the author of the first two editions of the dictionary.HistoryThe first edition was published in 1891 by West Publishing, with the full title A Dictionary of Law: containing definitions of the terms and phrases of American and English jurisprudence, ancient and modern, including the principal terms of international constitutional and commercial law, with a collection of legal maxims and numerous select titles from the civil law and other foreign systems. A second edition was published in 1910 as A Law Dictionary.

Robert I Estienne ( ; 15037 September 1559 ) , known as Robertus Stephanus in Latin and sometimes referred to as Robert Ier de Paris or Robertus Silvius , was an important French printer, editor and Huguenot . Stephanus was of Flemish origin. The family was originally from Spiere , now part of Belgium , but emigrated to France around 1400 . His father Simon was an important printer and publisher and his mother was the daughter of a silk maker. His brother Etienne and he both worked for a printer before Etienne left for Geneva and Robert went to Paris where he took over his father's business.

Stephen Arthur Cook , ( born December 14 , 1939 ) is an American-Canadian computer scientist and mathematician who has made important contributions to the fields of graph theory , combinatorics , computational learning theory , combinatorial design theory and computer science . His work includes the introduction of Boolean matrix conjecture (with R. H. Bremner ) and the probabilistic method of graph enumeration . In 1970, Cook became one of the first people to be hired in the computer science program at Simon Fraser University and one of the original faculty at the University of Western Ontario in the early 1970s.

Year 1233 (MCCXXXIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  War of the Lombards: Lombard forces at Kyrenia surrender to John of Beirut, after a 10-month siege. The defenders, with their personal belongings, are allowed to retire to Tyre. Prisoners captured, are exchanged for those held by Richard Filangieri, commander of the Lombards, at Tyre. Cyprus is wholly restored under the rule of the 16-year-old King Henry I (the Fat). His vassals are rewarded, and loans that they have made are repaid.

The French and Indian War ( 1754–1763 ) was a theater of the Seven Years ' War , which pitted the colonies of Britain against those of France , under the latter's European rival, France . ( The war also involved the German state of Prussia and several Native American tribes , and its American phase is sometimes called the Fourth Intercolonial War .) The war is so called in North America because, although the French and their Indian allies in the war lost , the British also lost the French and Indian War , and it is not widely known to most French .

In computer programming, a postcondition is a condition or predicate that must always be true just after the execution of some section of code or after an operation in a formal specification. Postconditions are sometimes tested using assertions within the code itself. Often, postconditions are simply included in the documentation of the affected section of code.For example: The result of a factorial is always an integer and greater than or equal to 1. So a program that calculates the factorial of an input number would have postconditions that the result after the calculation be an integer and that it be greater than or equal to 1.

Little is known of Memlings early life and training, the earliest records of his presence in the artistic life of Bruges, now in Belgium, are from 1464, when he was accepted into the Guild of Saint Luke as an apprentice.

Nvidia Corporation is an American multinational technology company incorporated in Delaware and based in Santa Clara , California . It designs, develops, and markets consumer graphics processing units ( GPUs), which are specialized high-performance processing units used in computer systems for visual and image rendering operations, and also professional graphics processing units ( GPUs) used in workstations and cloud-based data centers. In addition to GPUs, it also creates system on a chip (SoC) units which integrate both GPU and central processing units (CPUs) onto a single die, along with video processors, discrete GPUs, mobile computing processors, and semi-conductive laser diodes.

Mercia (, ; ) was one of the kingdoms of the Anglo-Saxon Heptarchy. The name is a Latinisation of the Old English  or  (West Saxon dialect;  in the Mercian dialect itself), meaning "border people" (see March). Mercia dominated what would later become England for three centuries, subsequently going into a gradual decline while Wessex eventually conquered and united all the kingdoms into the Kingdom of England.The kingdom was centred on the valley of the River Trent and its tributaries, in the region now known as the English Midlands. The court moved around the kingdom, and there was no fixed capital city.

A conjugate acid, within the Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory, is a  chemical compound formed when an acid donates a proton (H+) to a base—in other words, it is a base with a hydrogen ion added to it, as in the reverse reaction it loses a hydrogen ion. On the other hand, a conjugate base is what is left over after an acid has donated a proton during a chemical reaction. Hence, a conjugate base is a species formed by the removal of a proton from an acid, as in the reverse reaction it is able to gain a hydrogen ion.

Year 1390 (MCCCXC) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 19 – The Treaty of Lyck confirms an alliance between Vytautas and the Teutonic Knights, in the Lithuanian Civil War against Vytautas's cousin, Jogaila. April 14 – John VII Palaiologos overthrows his grandfather, John V Palaiologos, as Byzantine Emperor. April 19 – Robert III succeeds his father, Robert II, as King of Scotland. May 26 – Lithuanian Civil War: The Treaty of Königsberg is signed in Königsberg, between Samogitian nobles and representatives of the Teutonic Knights.

Proline (symbol Pro or P) is an organic acid classed as a proteinogenic amino acid (used in the biosynthesis of proteins), although it does not contain the amino group  but is rather a secondary amine. The secondary amine nitrogen is in the protonated NH2+ form under biological conditions, while the carboxyl group is in the deprotonated −COO− form. The "side chain" from the α carbon connects to the nitrogen forming a pyrrolidine loop, classifying it as a aliphatic amino acid. It is non-essential in humans, meaning the body can synthesize it from the non-essential amino acid L-glutamate.

Events  January–March  January 17 – Tuscarora War: Colonel James Moore leads the Carolina militia out of Albemarle County, North Carolina, in a second offensive against the Tuscarora. Heavy snows force the troops to take refuge in Fort Reading, on the Pamlico River. February 1 – Skirmish at Bender, Moldova: Charles XII of Sweden is defeated by the Ottoman Empire. February 4 – Tuscarora War: The Carolina militia under Colonel James Moore leaves Fort Reading, to continue the campaign against the Tuscarora. February 25 – Frederick William I of Prussia begins his reign.

Wenceslaus IV (also Wenceslas; ; , nicknamed "the Idle"; 26 February 136116 August 1419), also known as Wenceslaus of Luxembourg, was King of Bohemia from 1378 until his death and King of Germany from 1376 until he was deposed in 1400. As  he belonged to the House of Luxembourg, he was also Duke of Luxembourg from 1383 to 1388.BiographyWenceslaus was born in the Imperial city of Nuremberg, the son of Emperor Charles IV by his third wife Anna von Schweidnitz, a scion of the Silesian Piasts, and baptized at St. Sebaldus Church.

January 18–27 – James II of England is dethroned by the English parliament. January 31 – Battle of Khotyn : Charles V of Lorraine is defeated by the Ottoman Empire , but the Austrians come to the rescue of their ally. A playwright or dramatist is a person who writes plays.EtymologyThe word `` play '' is from Middle English pleye , which is from Old English pléagé (play, play-actor), which itself came from Old Norse pl & eacute;år (to toy, to play). The term was first used in English to describe a role in a morality play. The word `` dramatist '' is a noun derived from the term `drama ' which was from Classical Greek.The term `dramatist ' originally referred to the writer, actor or producer of a drama.

Wenceslaus IV ( also Wenceslas ; ; , nicknamed `` the Idle '' ; 26 February 136116 August 1419 ) was, from 1363, King of Bohemia (1378–1419), the first king of Bohemia of the Luxembourger dynasty, he also became the Bohemian anti-king in 1402. He was the eldest son of King Charles IV and he succeeded him in 1363. In 1373, Wenceslas became King of Naples. He reigned in that kingdom for four years, being the last king of the Angevin dynasty. In 1378 he became King of Bohemia.

Leisure Suit Larry is an adult-themed video game series created by Al Lowe. It was published by Sierra from 1987 to 2009, then by Codemasters starting in 2009. The first six Leisure Suit Larry titles, along with Magna Cum Laude and Love for Sail Mobile, were distributed by Vivendi Games (now Activision Blizzard), while Box Office Bust and Reloaded were distributed by Codemasters. Currently the games are being published and distributed by Assemble Entertainment.The games follow Larry Laffer, a balding, double entendre-speaking, leisure suit-wearing man in his 40s. The stories generally revolve around his attempting, usually unsuccessfully, to seduce attractive young women.

Year 1489 ( MCDLXXXIX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. January 20 – Mehmed II succeeds Bayezid II as Sultan of the Ottoman Empire. March 17 – The Inquisition is set up in Spain. April 30 – Treaty of Medina del Campo: King Ferdinand and Queen Isabella agree to help Columbus finance a voyage to Asia (the Indies) to open up trade with India. June 12 – Henry VII of England defeats his Yorkist enemies in the Battle of Bosworth Field, the last decisive battle of the Wars of the Roses.

The Fertile Crescent is a crescent-shaped region in the Middle East, spanning modern-day Iraq, Syria, Lebanon, Palestine, Israel, Jordan, and Northern Egypt, together with the northern region of Kuwait, southeastern region of Turkey and the western portion of Iran. Some authors also include Cyprus.The region is one of the cradles of civilization because it is one location where settled farming first emerged as people started the process of clearance and modification of natural vegetation to grow newly domesticated plants as crops. Early human civilizations such as Sumer in Mesopotamia flourished as a result.

Lead azide   is an inorganic compound. More so than other azides,  is explosive. It is used in detonators to initiate secondary explosives. In a commercially usable form, it is a white to buff powder.Preparation and handlingLead azide is prepared by the reaction of sodium azide and lead(II) nitrate in aqueous solution. Lead acetate can also be used.Thickeners such as dextrin or polyvinyl alcohol are often added to the solution to stabilize the precipitated product. In fact, it is normally shipped in a dextrinated solution that lowers its sensitivity.Production historyLead azide in its pure form was first prepared by Theodor Curtius in 1891.

Year 1182 (MCLXXXII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  April – Massacre of the Latins: The Roman Catholic (called "Latin") inhabitants of Constantinople massacre the Venetian, Genoan, and other Latin officials and traders who rule as agents of Empress Maria of Antioch. She is the mother and regent of 12-year-old Emperor Alexios II. In August, Andronikos Komnenos, a cousin of Maria's late husband, Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos), raises an army and enters the city, representing himself as the 'protector' of Alexios.

La Ruffiana is an older female character of the Commedia dell'Arte with a shady past or who used to be a courtesan but later reformed. The name derives from the Italian buffoon "Il Ruffiano" (1603), which means "the thief". As a character she is often associated with Zanni, but also plays the motherly role towards the Zanni character of the character Pierrot. She is sometimes called La Zannetta (the Zanni girl) or La Mattona ("the old bag"). She is a very cynical and opportunistic female character who will take any advantage that comes her way.

Year 1175 ( MCLXXV ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. 1.1.2 East Asia
1.3.2.1 Seljuk Civil War
3.1 May 15 – Battle of Eresing: Emperor Frederick I Barbarossa and Duke Henry the Lion defeat the Saxons. 4.1 May 16 – Pope Alexander III succeeds Pope Victor IV. 4.2 October 20 – The Battle of Myriokephalon takes place near Ptolemaida, between the Byzantine and Latin Empire forces. 5.1 The Cistercians establish the first monastery in England in Waverley. 6.1 The Khmer Empire begins to decline.

Operetta is a form of theatre and a genre of light opera . It includes spoken dialogue , songs , instrumental pieces, ballet and spectacle. Originally, " operetta " denoted a musical stage work without singing , akin to an opéra comique . Operetta was a significant art form in its day, and remains popular today . Many operetta works are still part of their creators ' active repertoire, with productions in Europe and the United States. Operetta is a fusion of the traditional opera (including opera buffa ), with the opéra comique and the German singspiel .

Year 1023 ( MXXIII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Year 1023 (MXXIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar. January 2 – Emperor Go-Reizei ascends the throne of Japan. April 8 – Battle of Melitene: The Byzantine army, led by the General Michael Bourtzes and Manuel, the brother of Romanos III Argyros, inflict the Seljuks under their Sultan Tughril I a crushing defeat. July 27 – The Council of Toulouse of the Catholic Church prohibits marriages between clergy and clergy widows.

Provincetown is a New England town located at the extreme tip of Cape Cod in Barnstable County , Massachusetts , United States. Its municipal population was 3,231 as of 2010 census, and it is the site of the Norman Mailer Home and Provincetown Municipal Airport. In 2012, Provincetown was ranked number one in the Top 10 Cape Cod and Islands beaches by TripAdvisor in its annual "Traveler's Choice" awards for beaches. Today Provincetown is a tourist destination known for its beaches, its art colony, and its place in history of the gay and lesbian rights movement.

Charles Pierce (July 14, 1926 – May 31, 1999) was one of the 20th century's foremost female impersonators, particularly noted for his impersonation of Bette Davis.Life and careerBorn in Watertown, New York, he began his show business career playing the organ and acting in radio dramas at station WWNY. He branched out into a comedy routine, attired in tuxedo, yet managing to evoke eerily convincing imitations of popular movie actresses. Eschewing the term drag queen, which he hated, he billed himself as a male actress.Initially playing in small gay clubs, his fame spread.

The Witan , literally `` wise men '' , was the king 's council in Anglo-Saxon England from before the Norman Conquest until the early twelfth century, and the court's highest council. Its name is a combination of Old English witan meaning `` wise man '' and the Old English noun wit , literally `` wisdom '' but meaning here `` counsel, advice ''. The witan was the successor of the Gewiten , a group that had probably existed in the kingdoms of Kent, Mercia, and East Anglia from the sixth century. The council was made up of the bishops, ealdormen, thegns, and other nobles.

.Year 1134 ( MCXXXIV ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. 1263 – The Statute of the Jewry of Lincoln is issued, defining the rights and obligations of Jewish residents. 1320 – First defenestration of Prague: A window in the Town Hall of Prague is allegedly opened and King Wenceslaus is thrown out. 1342 – The French army recovers three of the five fortified towns that had recently been lost to the English. 1429 – English forces capture Orléans, France, during the Hundred Years' War.

Year 1449 (MCDXLIX) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 6 – Constantine XI Palaiologos is crowned Byzantine Emperor at Mistra; he will be the last in a line of rulers that can be traced to the founding of Rome. February – Alexăndrel seizes the throne of Moldavia, with the support of the boyars. March 24 – Hundred Years' War: English capture Fougères in Brittany. April 7 – The last Antipope, Felix V, abdicates. April 19 – Pope Nicholas V is elected by the Council of Basel.

Juggling is a physical skill , performed by a juggler , involving the manipulation of objects for recreation , entertainment , artistic expression , or sport. For this reason, although the term is sometimes used to denote a specific subset of these, it is not recommended to define juggling by the number of objects used in a pattern. A person who practises juggling is typically called a juggler. Those who juggle items that are easily and cheaply replaceable, such as balls, typically do so to improve hand-eye coordination, dexterity , focus , and object control.

A horoscope ( or other commonly used names for the horoscope in English include natal chart , astrological chart , celestial map , vedic chart , natal diagram or natal chart ) is considered to be an astrologer ’s chart representing the positions of the Sun, Moon, planets, the astrologer’s chart, and the houses at the time of birth. The positions of the astrological bodies are often interpreted as indicative of various trends and factors affecting the chart native ’s character and prospects. House astrological interpretations
The astrological houses represent spheres of life in which a person experiences events and energies.

Year 1302 ( MCCCII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. 1405–1431 – The Hanseatic League gains control over Gotland, which becomes one of their principal trading centers. March – Battle of Roslin – King Edward I of England (nicknamed "Longshanks") is defeated by the forces of Andrew Moray and William Wallace. April 20 – Pope Benedict XI succeeds Pope Celestine V, after his unexpected abdication. September 10 – King Edward I of England fights his final battle against the Scots at Falkirk in Scotland.

Year 1525 (MDXXV) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 21 – The Swiss Anabaptist Movement is born when Conrad Grebel, Felix Manz, George Blaurock, and about a dozen others baptize each other in the home of Manz's mother on Neustadt-Gasse, Zürich, breaking a thousand-year tradition of church-state union. February 24 – Battle of Pavia: German and Spanish forces under Charles de Lannoy and the Marquis of Pescara defeat the French army, and capture Francis I of France, after his horse is wounded by Cesare Hercolani.

Bessarabia ( ; ; ; , Bessarabiya ; ; , Bessarabiya ; , Besarabiya ) is a historical region in Eastern Europe, centered on the lands of the former Principality of Moldavia (between the Dniester river and the lower Prut river), which is currently split between the Republic of Moldova (with the exception of one eastern part, which is located in Romania), the Russian Federation, and the Ukrainian SSR . Bessarabia is variously defined. The larger definition includes territory currently part of Ukraine , Russia's Moldavian Autonomous Republic , as well as most of Budjak .

Prince Igor is an opera in four acts with a prologue , written and composed by Alexander Borodin . The libretto was prepared by the composer and his friend, the critic and playwright Stepan Gedeonovsky, based on an early 12th-century Russian epic of the same name. The libretto of Prince Igor was finished by the time Borodin had composed most of the opera's music. However, the two men were reluctant to proceed, fearing that any libretto for the opera would be inadequate. In the end, they were persuaded by the theatre's new general manager, who gave them permission to compose the libretto as they went along.

Year 1401 ( MCDI ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. 1377 – The Battle of the Chelmsford Bridge is fought in Essex on April 25 between the armies of King Richard II and Thomas, Duke of Gloucester. The royalists are victorious and capture the duke. 1379 – Battle of Nibley Green is fought, between Ralph Stafford, 2nd Earl of Stafford and the Duke of Touraine, for the throne of the duchy of Guienne. 1401 ( 1401) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display full calendar ) of the Julian calendar.

Dengue fever is a mosquito-borne tropical disease caused by the dengue virus. Symptoms typically begin three to fourteen days after infection. These may include a high fever, headache, vomiting, muscle and joint pains, and a characteristic skin rash. Recovery generally takes two to seven days. In a small proportion of cases, the disease develops into a more severe dengue hemorrhagic fever, resulting in bleeding, low levels of blood platelets and blood plasma leakage, or into dengue shock syndrome, where dangerously low blood pressure occurs.Dengue is spread by several species of female mosquitoes of the Aedes genus, principally Aedes aegypti.

Year 1362 (MCCCLXII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 1 – The Grand Duchy of Lithuania switches New Year to January 1, before any other country does. January 16 – The "Grote Mandrenke" storm tide strikes the Netherlands, England, Germany and Denmark, destroying the Danish settlement of Rungholt in the Duchy of Schleswig, and the Humber estuary port of Ravenser Odd in England. The East Frisian island of Buise is broken into two by North Sea floods.

Year 1370 (MCCCLXX) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 9 – Timur becomes first Amir of the Timurid Empire, following the Siege of Balkh which establishes his rule over the Chagatai Khanate, completing his conquest of Central Asia and parts of Persia. May 24 – The Treaty of Stralsund ends the war between Denmark and the Hanseatic League. September 19 – Hundred Years' War: Siege of Limoges – The English led by Edward the Black Prince retake the city from the French by storm with wide destruction, effectively ending the Limoges enamel industry.

Year 1193 ( MCXCIII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. 1267 years ago (1212 BC) – Battle of Kadesh. 1212 years ago (480 BC) – Battle of Salamis: Greek city-states defeat Persia in a decisive naval battle of the Greco-Persian War. 1012 years ago (871) – The Siege of Jerusalem (871-873): the city is captured from the Abbasid Caliphate by the armies of the Prince of Aleppo. 1130 years ago (1363 AD) – Battle of Sufetula.

Year 1556 ( MDLVI ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. At the time, it was known as the Year of the Pig . January 1 – In accordance with the Compromise of Augsburg , the Augsburg Confession, a key confession of Lutheran faith, is approved by Holy Roman Emperor Charles V . February 9 – French troops land in Calais during the siege of Boulogne. February 11 – Bishop of Gloucester John Hooper (1522–57) is imprisoned at Newgate prison, London.

The Polish People's Party (, PSL) is an agrarian political party in Poland. It is currently led by Władysław Kosiniak-Kamysz.Its history traces back to 1895, when it held the name People's Party, although its name was changed to the present one in 1903. During the Second Polish Republic, the Polish People's Party was represented by a number of parties that held its name. They were all supportive of agrarian policies, although they spanned from the left-wing to the centre-right on the political spectrum. It was reformed into the People's Party shortly after the Sanacja regime took power.

The Commonwealth Games , often referred to as the Friendly Games , is an international multi-sport event involving athletes from the Commonwealth of Nations . The event was first held in 1930, and serves as a kind of successor to the 19th century (British) colonies' event , the now defunct British Empire Games (or the Imperial Games). The Games take place every four years, just like the Olympics . The 2010 games were held in Delhi, India between 3rd October and 14th October and the next games will be in 2014 in Glasgow, Scotland.

In mathematics , an -sphere or a hypersphere is a topological space that is homeomorphic to a standard -sphere , i.e., a space that can be obtained from by removing a small open ball. In this definition, the term "small" is not specified, but typically means bounded in terms of the given metrics . In the context of this definition, an -ball is called an intrinsic ball . In addition to the topological notions, a variety of metrics can be attached to a space that is locally homeomorphic to . In geometric topology, -spheres are sometimes called -dimensional pseudospheres.

A sifaka   is a lemur of the genus Propithecus from the family Indriidae within the order Primates. The name of their family is an onomatopoeia of their characteristic "shi-fak" alarm call. Like all lemurs, they are found only on the island of Madagascar. All species of sifakas are threatened, ranging from endangered to critically endangered.Anatomy and physiology Sifakas are medium-sized indrids with a head and body length of  and a weight of . Their tail is just as long as their body, which differentiates them from the Indri. Their fur is long and silky, with coloration varying by species from yellowish-white to blackish-brown.

Eleusine coracana, or finger millet, also known as ragi in India, kodo in Nepal, is an annual herbaceous plant widely grown as a cereal crop in the arid and semiarid areas in Africa and Asia. It is a tetraploid and self-pollinating species probably evolved from its wild relative Eleusine africana.Finger millet is native to the Ethiopian and Ugandan highlands. Interesting crop characteristics of finger millet are the ability to withstand cultivation at altitudes over 2000 m above sea level, its high drought tolerance, and the long storage time of the grains.History Finger millet originated in East Africa (Ethiopian and Ugandan highlands).

Year 1217 (MCCXVII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Fifth Crusade  Summer – Various groups of French knights reach the Italian ports. King Andrew II of Hungary arrives with his army in Split, in Dalmatia. He is joined by German forces, led by Duke Leopold VI (the Glorious). At the end of July, Pope Honorius III orders the crusaders assembled in Italy and Sicily to proceed to Cyprus, but there is no transport provided by the Italian city-states, Venice, Genoa and Pisa.

Year 1470 (MCDLXX) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 12 – Wars of the Roses in England – Battle of Losecoat Field: The House of York defeats the House of Lancaster. March 20 (Julian calendar) – The Battle of Nibley Green is the last fought between the private armies of feudal magnates in England. Spring: Anglo-Hanseatic War: Hanseatic League privateers set sail. May 15 – Charles VIII of Sweden, who has served three terms as King of Sweden, dies.

Palermo ( , ;  , locally also  or ; , from ; older ) is a city in southern Italy, the capital of both the autonomous region of Sicily and the Metropolitan City of Palermo, the city's surrounding metropolitan province. The city is noted for its history, culture, architecture and gastronomy, playing an important role throughout much of its existence; it is over 2,700 years old. Palermo is in the northwest of the island of Sicily, by the Gulf of Palermo in the Tyrrhenian Sea.The city was founded in 734 BC by the Phoenicians as  ("flower").
