Year 1357 ( MCCCLVII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. 1490 – King Henry VII is crowned the King of England. 1504 – Michelangelo's David is unveiled in Piazza della Signoria in Florence . 1800 – John Marshall is appointed Chief Justice of the United States. 1911 – The Republic of China is founded, succeeding the Xinhai Revolution which overthrew the Qing Dynasty. 1920 – The Anastenaria Pentecost festival is held in Macedonia . 1942 – The first issue of the Polish underground newspaper Krypta is published.

In physics , quintessence is a hypothetical form of dark energy , more precisely a scalar field , postulated as a solution to some problems encountered with the standard ΛCDM model , particularly with its assumption that the universe is spatially flat in which the density of matter varies slowly with time . In a theory where dark energy density varies by orders of magnitude, the universe should have either expanded more quickly in the past and slowed down more dramatically now, or else accelerated more rapidly in recent times. If matter density varies with time, the expansion rate of the universe could also change by a factor of a thousand.

Events < onlyinclude > January–June January 17 – The Treaty of Königsberg is signed , establishing an alliance between Charles XII , King of Sweden , and Augustus II, King of Poland ( Elector of Saxony). February 27 – Swedish forces defeat the Russians at the Battle of Narva. April–May – In the Battle of Klissow , Augustus forces are decisively beaten by Charles XII's troops, who take Kraków. May 4 – Emperor Go-Mizunoo abdicates in favor of his son, who becomes the Emperor Reigen. May 15 – A peace treaty between Russia and Poland is signed.

Year 1406 (MCDVI) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 4 – James I becomes King of Scotland, after having been captured by Henry IV of England. October 7 – French troops comprising 1,000 men at arms land on Jersey, and fight a battle against 3,000 defenders. October 13 – Richard Whittington is elected Lord Mayor of London for a second full term. He holds this office simultaneously, with that of Mayor of the Calais Staple. October 26 – Eric of Pomerania marries Philippa, daughter of Henry IV of England.

Year 1332 (MCCCXXXII) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  February 18 – Amda Seyon I, Emperor of Ethiopia, begins his campaigns in the southern Muslim provinces (possibly in 1329). August 10–11 – Battle of Dupplin Moor: Edward Balliol rebels, and the English defeat the loyalists of David II in Scotland. September – Edward Balliol crowns himself King of Scotland. November 7 – Lucerne joins the Swiss Confederation with Uri, Schwyz, and Unterwalden. December 16 – Battle of Annan: The loyalists of David II defeat Edward Balliol in Scotland.

J. Robert Oppenheimer ( ; April 22 , 1904 – February 18 , 1967 ) was an American theoretical physicist and professor of physics . He is best known for his work as the director of the Los Alamos Laboratory where the first atomic bombs were developed and his role in the Manhattan Project . He studied at Cambridge and Berkeley and taught at Berkeley and the University of Minnesota . He advised President Lyndon B. Johnson on nuclear weapons . Oppenheimer was a left-winger before the Second World War but his political loyalties were unclear during this war.

A killer is someone or something that kills , such as a murderer or a serial killer . Killer or Killers or The Killer can also be used for other things that kill such as weapons. Killer is also a noun which means a very popular or fashionable person or thing. A serial killer is someone who kills several times over a period of time. Most serial killers select their victims at random. Someone who kills animals to make their fur coats is called a fur killer. Someone who kills all the animals in the food chain is called a killer of all species.

DeCSS is one of the first free computer programs capable of decrypting content on a commercially produced DVD video disc. Before the release of DeCSS, open source operating systems (such as BSD and Linux) could not play encrypted video DVDs.DeCSS's development was done without a license from the DVD Copy Control Association (CCA), the organization responsible for DVD copy protection—namely, the Content Scramble System (CSS) used by commercial DVD publishers. The release of DeCSS resulted in a Norwegian criminal trial and subsequent acquittal of one of the authors of DeCSS.

Epicureanism is a system of philosophy founded around 307 BC based upon the teachings of the ancient Greek philosopher Epicurus. The philosophy is a materialistic form of skepticism. The principal idea of the doctrine was that the chief goods were sensory pleasures, especially immediate pleasures and pleasures of intercourse with friends, family, and fellow citizens, while evil was pain, disease and death. Pleasure and pain comprised the only criteria of goodness or badness and the standard to be used in resolving doubts about ethical matters, with pain as the superior.

Year 1022 (MXXII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Battle of Svindax: The Byzantine army under Emperor Basil II defeats the Georgians at Svindax (modern Turkey). King George I is forced to negotiate a peace treaty, ending the Byzantine–Georgian wars. Summer – Nikephoros Phokas (Barytrachelos) conspires with the Byzantine general Nikephoros Xiphias against Basil II. The rebellion collapses and Xiphias assassinates Phokas. Europe  Spring – Emperor Henry II divides his army into three columns and descends through Rome onto Capua.

Short-track speed skating is a form of competitive ice speed skating. In competitions, multiple skaters (typically between four and six) skate on an oval ice track with a length of . The rink itself is  long by  wide, which is the same size as an Olympic-sized figure skating rink and an international-sized ice hockey rink. Related sports include long track speed skating and inline speed skating.HistoryShort-track skating developed from speed skating events that were held with mass starts. This form of speed skating was mainly practised in the United States and Canada, as opposed to the international form, where athletes skated in pairs.

Year 1148 (MCXLVIII) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place   Second Crusade  January 1 – The French crusaders under King Louis VII defeat a Turkish ambush next to the Meander River. Three days later they arrive at Laodicea – passing the spot where the German contingent led by Otto of Freising has been so disastrously ambushed (see 1147). The Crusaders are badly mauled as they cross Mount Cadmus (around January 8) before reaching Adalia on January 20.

The foreign relations of Albania are its relations with other governments and peoples . Foreign relations are conducted through the Ministry of Foreign Affairs. After the restoration of the monarchy in 1913, during the Balkan Wars, the Albanian government conducted a diplomacy which was in accord with its geographical and historical conditions, and which was also directed against Serbia. In the First World War, Albania maintained neutrality. Albania's first king, Zog, had an active diplomacy during his 1928 to 1939 tenure, and his wife was a scion of the Russian imperial family. The country joined the Anti-Comintern Pact in 1941.

Sultan Al-Kamil, in command of the Egyptian forces, is almost overthrown by a conspiracy in his entourage. He considers fleeing to the Ayyubid Emirate of Yemen, ruled by his son Al-Mas'ud Yusuf, but the arrival of his brother Al-Mu'azzam with reinforcements from Syria, ends the conspiracy.

In physics , optical depth or optical thickness is the natural logarithm of the ratio of incident to transmitted radiant power per unit area per unit of frequency per unit thickness in a direction of constant density. The units can be the watts (W) per steradians per square metre or the watts per steradians per meter per hertz (frequency per steradians per meter); the SI system has the second form. The term optical thickness is commonly used in atmospheric and astronomical research in the context of scattering media, as an empirical substitute for the more precise and complicated definition given above.

The Motorola MC68010 processor is a 16/32-bit microprocessor from Motorola, released in 1982 as the successor to the Motorola 68000. It fixes several small flaws in the 68000, and adds a few features.The 68010 is pin-compatible with the 68000, but is not 100% software compatible. Some of the differences were: The MOVE from SR instruction is now privileged (it may only be executed in supervisor mode). This means that the 68010 meets Popek and Goldberg virtualization requirements. Because the 68000 offers an unprivileged MOVE from SR, it does not meet them.

The 12th century BC is the period from 1200 to 1101 BC. The Late Bronze Age collapse in the ancient Near East and eastern Mediterranean is often considered to begin in this century.Events 1200 BC: The first civilization in Central and North America develops in about 1200 BC in the coastal regions of the southern part of the Gulf of Mexico. Known as the Olmec civilization, its early site is at San Lorenzo. 1200 BC: The Phoenicians found the port of Lisbon, Portugal 1197 BC: The beginning of the first period (1197 BC – 982 BC) by Shao Yong's concept of the I Ching and history.

In mathematics, an -sphere or a hypersphere is a topological space that is homeomorphic to a standard -sphere, which is the set of points in -dimensional Euclidean space that are situated at a constant distance  from a fixed point, called the center. It is the generalization of an ordinary sphere in the ordinary three-dimensional space. The "radius" of a sphere is the constant distance of its points to the center. When the sphere has unit radius, it is usual to call it the unit -sphere or simply the -sphere for brevity.

Events  January–June  January 14 – Portuguese Restoration War – Battle of the Lines of Elvas: The Portuguese beat the Spanish. January 24 – Pierre Corneille's Oedipe premieres in Paris. February 2 – Jan van Riebeeck produces the first South African wine, at the Cape of Good Hope. February 11 – The Assault on Copenhagen by Swedish forces is beaten back, with heavy losses. February 16 – The first known cheque (400 pounds) is written. April 22 – Lord Protector Richard Cromwell dissolves the English Parliament. May 21 – The Kingdom of France, the Commonwealth of England and the Dutch Republic sign the Concert of The Hague.

Three bobsleigh events were competed at the 2002 Winter Olympics, at Utah Olympic Park. The competition took place between February 16 and February 23, 2002.For the first time since 1932, Olympic bobsleigh added a new event, with the first ever women's competition, won by Jill Bakken and  Vonetta Flowers of the United States.The competitions comprised four heats. Teams raced in the first and third heats in the order of the draw. The second heat was raced in order of ranking after the first heat, and the fourth heat is raced in order of the ranking after the first three heats.

Year 1150 (MCL) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Battle of Tara: The Byzantines defeat the Serbian-Hungarian army under Grdeša, count (župan) of Travunija, near the snow-covered Tara River. The Serbs are overpowered, and Grand Prince Uroš II is forced to accept the peace agreement made by Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos). Uroš is succeeded by his brother Desa, who  becomes co-ruler of the Principality of Serbia (until 1153).

In software quality assurance, performance testing is in general a testing practice performed to determine how a system performs in terms of responsiveness and stability under a particular workload. It can also serve to investigate, measure, validate or verify other quality attributes of the system, such as scalability, reliability and resource usage.Performance testing, a subset of performance engineering, is a computer science practice which strives to build performance standards into the implementation, design and architecture of a system.Testing typesLoad testing Load testing is the simplest form of performance testing. A load test is usually conducted to understand the behavior of the system under a specific expected load.

In the performing arts, a scenario (, ; from Italian: "that which is pinned to the scenery", ) is a synoptical collage of an event or series of actions and events. In the commedia dell'arte it was an outline of entrances, exits, and action describing the plot of a play, and was literally pinned to the back of the scenery. It is also known as canovaccio  or "that which is pinned to the canvas" of which the scenery was constructed.Surviving scenarios from the Renaissance contain little other than character names, brief descriptions of action, and references to specific lazzi with no further explanation.

OCaml ( , formerly Objective Caml ) is a general-purpose , multi-paradigm programming language which extends the Caml dialect of the ML family of types. OCaml is an imperative and functional programming language. Its design philosophy stresses functional programming; however, an object system and a typeclass mechanism were added after the first release of the language, extending it to the multi-paradigm style. OCaml provides built-in polymorphic variants and records, and powerful functional-programming abstractions such as maps (associative arrays) and arrays. The programming language is intended to be easy to learn, and to support the development of large applications.

Year 1579 (MDLXXIX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar, and a common year starting on Monday of the Proleptic Gregorian calendar.Events  January–June  January 6  – The Union of Arras unites the southern Netherlands under the Duke of Parma, governor in the name of king Philip II of Spain. January 23 –  The Union of Utrecht unites the northern Netherlands in a confederation called the United Provinces. William I of Orange becomes Stadtholder, and the Duc d'Anjou, younger brother of Henry III of France, is invited to become hereditary sovereign.

Margaret ( , ; March or April 1283 – September 1290 ) , known as the Maid of Norway , was the only child of Erling 2nd of Norway and his wife Margarete , daughter of Alexander III of Scotland . She was Queen of Scotland from 1284 until her death in 1290 , and she became Queen of Norway in 1287. Margaret was born at Tønsberg in Norway. The future king of Norway was also born the same year, Haakon IV Magnusson. When she was a child, her parents, King Eric II and Queen Margaret were deposed and she became the ruler of Scotland.

April 5 – Battle of Tiexiang : Song Dynasty forces, led by Song Qianzong and Zeng Gong, are defeated by forces of the rebel Qidan tribe led by Yelü Dule. Events  January–June  January–June – The Swiss Peasant War is fought. January 3 – By the Coonan Cross Oath, the Eastern Church in India cuts itself off from colonial Portuguese tutelage. February 2 – New Amsterdam (later renamed New York City) is incorporated. February 3 – Cardinal Mazarin returns to Paris from exile. March 14 – A Dutch fleet defeats the English in the Battle of Leghorn; the Dutch commander, Johan van Galen, later dies of his wounds. April 20 – Oliver Cromwell expels the Rump Parliament in England.

Year 1213 (MCCXIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  May 15 – King John of England submits to Pope Innocent III, who in turn lifts the interdict of 1208. May 30 – Battle of Damme: The English fleet under William Longespée, 3rd Earl of Salisbury, destroys a French fleet off the Belgian port in the first major victory for the fledgling Royal Navy. September 12 – Battle of Muret: The Toulousain and Aragonese forces of Raymond VI of Toulouse and Peter II of Aragon are defeated by the Albigensian Crusade, under Simon de Montfort.

Casimir IV (in full Casimir IV Andrew Jagiellon;  ; Lithuanian: ; 30 November 1427 – 7 June 1492) was Grand Duke of Lithuania from 1440 and King of Poland from 1447, until his death. He was one of the most active Polish-Lithuanian rulers, under whom Poland, by defeating the Teutonic Knights in the Thirteen Years' War recovered Pomerania, and the Jagiellonian dynasty became one of the leading royal houses in Europe.The great triumph of his reign was bringing Prussia under Polish rule. The rule of Casimir corresponded to the age of "new monarchies" in western Europe.

Louis I , also Louis the Great ( ; ; ) or Louis the Hungarian ( ; 5 March 132610 September 1382 ) was King of Hungary and Croatia between 1342 and 1382 . He was crowned King of Hungary after his father-in-law and predecessor, King Charles I, was assassinated. After his cousin Casimir III of Poland died without a son in 1370, Louis gained the Polish throne and became de facto king of Poland as Louis I. He was the first monarch of both Poland and Hungary since 1025. After he died, the countries were ruled by separate dynasties.

Three bobsleigh events were competed at the 2002 Winter Olympics , at Utah Olympic Park . The competition took place between 16 and 17 February, 2002, with the 4-man bob first. The medals were awarded on 17 February. The German team won three of the four gold medals, with André Lange, David Möller, Enrico Kühn and Alexander Rädle in the 4-man event and Sandra Kiriasis and Sylke Otto, with team-mates Barbara Niedernhuber and Christian Poser, taking the two 2-woman gold medals. The United States won the other 4-man title as Brian Shimer's team beat the Swiss and German teams.

Before October – Sultan Mehmed II of the Ottoman Empire is forced to abdicate, in favor of his father Murad II, by the Janissaries.

The Laboratory for Atmospheric and Space Physics (LASP) is a research organization at the University of Colorado Boulder. LASP is a research institute with over one hundred research scientists ranging in fields from solar influences, to Earth's and other planetary atmospherics processes, space weather, space plasma and dusty plasma physics. LASP has advanced technical capabilities specializing in designing, building, and operating spacecraft and spacecraft instruments.HistoryFounded after World War II, the first scientific instruments built at LASP were launched into space using captured German V-2 rockets. To this day LASP continues a suborbital rocket program through periodic calibration instrument flights from White Sands Missile Range.

New England Digital Corporation (1976–1993) was founded in Norwich, Vermont, and relocated to White River Junction, Vermont. It was best known for its signature product, the Synclavier Synthesizer System, which evolved into the Synclavier Digital Audio System or "Tapeless Studio." The company sold an FM digital synthesizer/16-bit polyphonic synthesizer and magnetic disk-based non-linear 16-bit digital recording product, referred to as the "Post-Pro." The Synclavier was developed as the "Dartmouth Digital Synthesizer" by Dartmouth College Professors Jon Appleton and Frederick J. Hooven, in association with NED co-founders Sydney A. Alonso and Cameron W. Jones.

Business is the activity of making one's living or making money by producing or buying and selling products (such as goods and services). Simply put, it is "any activity or enterprise entered into for profit. "Having a business name does not separate the business entity from the owner, which means that the owner of the business is responsible and liable for debts incurred by the business. If the business acquires debts, the creditors can go after the owner's personal possessions. A business structure does not allow for corporate tax rates.

The Cathedral of St. John the Divine ( sometimes referred to as St. John 's and also nicknamed St. John 's) is one of New York City 's Cathedral churchs in Manhattan. It is a Gothic Revival masterwork by architect Heins and Lafarge, one of New York 's finest architectural examples. It has been under construction since 1890 and its completion has been anticipated since 2008. The cathedral's Episcopal bishop, the Rt Rev. Andrew M.L. Dietsche, calls the building a "great house of the soul" for all religions.

He fights over the control of Maine (after the death of Count Hugh IV), and lays siege to the fortresses of Alençon and Domfront (Western France). May 19 – King Henry I of France marries Anne of Kiev at the cathedral of Reims. Mariner 2 ( Mariner-Venus 1962 ) , an American space probe to Venus , was the first robotic space probe to successfully perform a planetary fly-by. A series of five space probes that used Venus as a launching pad to the outer planets, Mariner-Venus was the first. Mariner 2 was launched in 1962. Mariner 1, a backup, was destroyed on launch pad 1. Mariner 2, designed for a Venus flyby, was the fifth member of the Mariner series of space probes and the first to succeed in a planetary flyby (the previous four members had either failed to launch or had failed en route to their targets).

Year 1210 ( MCCX ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. 1191–1210: Al-Mansur Qala'un (Qala'un), of the Ayyubid Dynasty, was ruler of the Ayyubid state, with his capital at Cairo, Egypt. The Ayyubid dynasty was established by Saladin's son, Al-Aziz Uthman, who founded the state in the wake of the defeat of the army of the Zengid Dynasty in Egypt. Al-Kamil was a Sultan of the Ayyubid dynasty, who ruled Egypt from 1218 to his death.

The Asian Games, also known as Asiad, is a continental multi-sport event held every four years among athletes from all over Asia. The Games were regulated by the Asian Games Federation (AGF) from the first Games in New Delhi, India, until the 1978 Games. Since the 1982 Games, they have been organized by the Olympic Council of Asia (OCA), after the breakup of the Asian Games Federation. The Games are recognized by the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and are described as the second largest multi-sport event after the Olympic Games.There have been nine nations that have hosted the Asian Games.

It orders that the Book of Common Prayer 1552 shall be the sole form of public worship, but makes some minor allowances. January 27 – The Piedmontese army is defeated at the Battle of Caravaggio , forcing them to retire from the Spanish–Franco–Habsburg theater. February 5 – In England, the House of Lords passes the Tonnage and Poundage Act, and the Petition of Right. April 10 – The Long Parliament votes to impeach the King of England.

July 24–September 15 – The Battle of La Rochelle is a naval confrontation between England and France, that takes place at sea near La Rochelle in the English Channel, and ends with a French naval victory. August 28 – John Wycliffe, the first English reformer, is summoned by Pope Gregory XI before the Inquisition, but is dismissed on account of illness.

Year 1327 (MCCCXXVII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 25 – The 14-year-old Edward III is proclaimed King of England, after his mother Isabella has engineered the abdication of his imprisoned father Edward II of England, on January 20, effective January 25. Isabella and her lover Roger Mortimer rule as regents (the coronation takes place February 1). April 6 (Good Friday) – Tuscan writer Petrarch sees a woman he names Laura in the church of Sainte-Claire d'Avignon, which awakes in him a lasting passion.

Mary Virginia Martin (December 1, 1913 – November 3, 1990) was an American actress and singer. A muse of Rodgers and Hammerstein, she originated many leading roles on stage over her career, including Nellie Forbush in South Pacific (1949), the title character in Peter Pan (1954), and Maria von Trapp in The Sound of Music (1959). She was named a Kennedy Center Honoree in 1989. She was the mother of actor Larry Hagman.Early life Martin was born in Weatherford, Texas. Her autobiography described her childhood as secure and happy.

Frederick (Middle High German: Friderich, Standard German: Friedrich; 21 September 1371 – 20 September 1440) was the last Burgrave of Nuremberg from 1397 to 1427 (as Frederick VI), Margrave of Brandenburg-Ansbach from 1398, Margrave of Brandenburg-Kulmbach from 1420, and Elector of Brandenburg (as Frederick I) from 1415 until his death. He became the first member of the House of Hohenzollern to rule the Margraviate of Brandenburg.Biography Frederick was born in Nuremberg, the second-born son of Burgrave Frederick V (1333–1398) and the Wettin princess Elisabeth of Meissen.

Year 1439 ( MCDXXXIX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar . The year 1439 is reckoned according to the Alexandrian Era , the year 6659 of the Byzantine / Constantinopolitan Era , and the fifth year of the Korean era . The Ottoman Empire makes peace with Venice , ending their 10-year war . Pope Pius II publishes his treatise De Judaeis (On Jews). Niccolò dell'Arca is appointed the first podesta of Florence. In France , Jeanne d'Arc is put on trial for witchcraft.

The European bison ( Bison bonasus ) or the European wood bison , also known as the wisent ( or wissant ) is a Eurasian species of ox in the family Bovidae; it is closely related to the American bison . The European bison is classified as an endangered species , with between 2000 and 2200 left in the wild. The European bison is a vulnerable species. This article is about a wild species. For domesticated species of bison , see bison . There are three living subspecies, one of which, the wisent, was reintroduced into the wild following extinction.

Frederick II of Brandenburg  (19 November 1413 – 10 February 1471), nicknamed "the Iron" (der Eiserne) and sometimes "Irontooth" (Eisenzahn), was a Prince-elector of the Margraviate of Brandenburg from 1440 until his abdication in 1470, and was a member of the House of Hohenzollern.BiographyFrederick II was born at Tangermünde Castle (German: Burg Tangermünde), when Tangermünde was within the Margraviate of Brandenburg, to Frederick I, Brandenburg's first Hohenzollern ruler, and his wife Elizabeth, daughter of Frederick, Duke of Bavaria-Landshut, and Maddalena Visconti.

Year 1355 ( MCCCLV ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Julian calendar of the Middle Ages. 1355 1359 1366 Year 1359 1366 Events January 1 – King Alfonso XI of Castile dies after a campaign against the Portuguese, without leaving an heir. His sister, Maria, is proclaimed Queen, but the throne is contested by Peter, Duke of Coimbria, who is supported by a party of nobles and bishops who are hostile to Alfonso's wife, Leonor Telles de Meneses, and wish to seize control of the throne of Castile.

In software quality assurance , performance testing is in general a testing practice performed to determine how a system performs under a particular workload. In a business environment, it is important to know how a system performs when the system will be used to execute certain functions in a real work situation. In performance testing the tester runs a test script on the system for a specific time period. This time period is called the "duration" for this test. This test script runs through a number of cycles and generates a huge volume of data which is then later analyzed.

Berchtesgaden  is a municipality in the district Berchtesgadener Land, Bavaria, in southeastern Germany, near the border with Austria,  south of Salzburg and  southeast of Munich. It lies in the Berchtesgaden Alps, south of Berchtesgaden; the Berchtesgaden National Park stretches along three parallel valleys.The Kehlstein mountain , with its Kehlsteinhaus (Eagle's Nest) is located in the area.EtymologyBerchtesgaden, Upper Bavaria (Achental), earlier Perchterscadmen, Perhtersgadem, Berchirchsgadem, Berchtoldesgadem; the word underwent a Latin distortion of Old High German parach, Romance bareca 'hay shed'.

Events  January–June  January 11 – The Cortes of Castile approves a new subsidy, the millones. March – Maurice of Nassau, Prince of Orange, takes Breda, by concealing 68 of his best men in a peat-boat, to get through the impregnable defences. March 14 – Battle of Ivry: Henry IV of France again defeats the forces of the Catholic League, under Charles, Duke of Mayenne. May–August – Henry IV of France unsuccessfully attempts to besiege Paris. Henry is forced to raise the siege, when Alexander Farnese, Duke of Parma comes to its rescue with a Spanish army.

Winter sports or winter activities are competitive sports or non-competitive recreational activities which are played on snow or ice . The athletes who are participating in winter sports usually wear special boots. Some winter sports are bobsleigh, skiing , snowboarding , curling , ice hockey , luge and snowshoeing . Some non-competitive activities which can be considered as a winter sports are ice fishing , snowmobiling and skijoring . The winter sports are often played in winter because they can be played only on ice or snow and because they are usually not played during the warmest parts of the year.

Cooking bananas are banana cultivars in the genus Musa whose fruits are generally used in cooking. They may be eaten ripe or unripe and are generally starchy. Many cooking bananas are referred to as plantains (/ˈplæntɪn/ US: /plænˈteɪn/,UK: /ˈplɑːntɪn/) or green bananas. In botanical usage, the term "plantain" is used only for true plantains, while other starchy cultivars used for cooking are called "cooking bananas". True plantains are cultivars belonging to the AAB Group, while cooking bananas are any cultivars belonging to AAB, AAA, ABB, or BBB groups.

Dub mac Maíl Coluim ( Modern Gaelic : Dubh mac Mhaoil Chaluim , ) , sometimes anglicised as Duff MacMalcolm, was king of Scotland from 1058 until his death. He was a son of Malcolm II and his second wife , Ingibiorg , the daughter of Finn Arnesson , King of Dublin , and his queen, Gormlaith of Leinster , daughter of Murrough of Leinster . Dub was the youngest of five sons. He was the only one not to become king and is believed to have been killed by his brother, Duncan I, in battle in 1034 at Pitgaveny , near Elgin, Scotland.

A semi-automatic rifle is an autoloading rifle that fires one round each pull of the trigger . For comparison , bolt action firearm is a type of single- barrel rifle and other firearm that employs a breech- loading method in which the spent casing is removed from the breech and replaced with a fresh cartridge in between the trigger pulls. The United States and Mexico share an extensive border of 2,100 miles and are the only two countries on the planet that share a fully open border, that is, without any legal impediments for citizens to pass back and forth across the line, according to the Washington Times.

Black 's Law Dictionary is the most widely used law dictionary in the United States . Henry Campbell Black (May 1, 1860 – July 19,1927) was born near Urbana, Ohio , attended the University of Michigan and then graduated from Harvard Law School in 1882. He went to work in Washington, D.C. as a law clerk for the United States Court of Claims. He worked there for six years, and during his years there, he became a close associate of a number of important jurists, lawyers and legislators. In 1887 he started his own firm and specialized in corporate law, taxes and international law.

Year 1445 (MCDXLV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  October 10 – Battle of Mokra: The Albanian forces under Skanderbeg defeat the Ottoman forces (Pope Eugene IV raises a hymn of praise, that Christendom has been provided with a new defender, after he hears of the battle). Date unknown  The Portuguese set up their first trading post (Feitoria) in Africa, on the island of Arguin. Portuguese explorer Dinis Dias discovers the Cap-Vert, on the western coast of Africa.

Roger Williams (21 December 1603between 27 January and 15 March 1683) was a Puritan minister, theologian, and author who founded Providence Plantations, which became the Colony of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations and later the U.S. State of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations, now the State of Rhode Island. He was a staunch advocate for religious freedom, separation of church and state, and fair dealings with Native Americans.Williams was expelled by the Puritan leaders from the Massachusetts Bay Colony and established Providence Plantations in 1636 as a refuge offering what he termed "liberty of conscience."

The transport in Azerbaijan involves air traffic , waterways and railroads . All transportation services in Azerbaijan except for oil transport are controlled by the Ministry for Transport. Azerbaijan's rail network extends 2,410 km. Azerbaijan has a railway connecting the capital Baku to Turkey, which passes through the city of Ganja . A railway connecting the capital Baku to Russia is currently under construction and is planned to be completed in 2015. This railway will extend to Aktau , Turkmenistan, through Georgia. The railway line connecting Baku to Russia, which passes through the Central Asia countries of Kazakhstan and Uzbekistan, is currently closed and in need of reconstruction.

Year 1344 (MCCCXLIV) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 26 – Reconquista: The Siege of Algeciras (1342–44), one of the first European military engagements where gunpowder is used, ends with the Muslim city of Algeciras surrendering and being incorporated into the Kingdom of Castile. April 17 – Constantine II, King of Armenia, is killed in an uprising and succeeded by a distant cousin, Constantine III. April 23 – The St. George's Night Uprising: The Livonian Order hangs Vesse, the rebel Estonian Elder of Saaremaa Island.

Toktar Ongarbayuly Aubakirov ( (Toqtar Oñğarbaiūly Äubäkırov), , born on 27 July 1946) is a retired Kazakh Air Force officer and a former cosmonaut. He is the first person from Kazakhstan to go to space.Early lifeToktar Aubakirov was born in Karkaraly district, Karaganda region, Kazakh SSR, which is now Kazakhstan. After graduating from the 8th grade of a secondary school he started working as a metal turner at the Temirtau foundry, whilst attending an evening school. In 1965 he joined the Armavir Military Aviation Institute of the Anti-Air Defence Pilots.

A trisomy is a type of polysomy in which there are three instances of a particular chromosome, instead of the normal two. A trisomy is a type of aneuploidy (an abnormal number of chromosomes).Description and causesMost organisms that reproduce sexually have pairs of chromosomes in each cell, with one chromosome inherited from each parent. In such organisms, a process called meiosis creates cells called gametes (eggs or sperm) that have only one set of chromosomes. The number of chromosomes is different for different species. Humans have 46 chromosomes (i.e. 23 pairs of chromosomes).

1412 – 1485) was one of the greatest scholars of the medieval Islam. His works had considerable effect on the Renaissance in the West, and on modern scholarship. He was born and died in 1412 (or 1414) in Tabriz (then in Persia). He made a study of the Qur'an that was unmatched by any other before his time or for some time afterwards. His commentaries are still consulted today and are considered highly accurate.

("No one shall throw with snowballs, neither men nor (unmarried) women.") Date unknown  The first printed edition of Dante Alighieri's Divine Comedy is published in Foligno.

Freestyle skiing is a skiing discipline comprising aerials , moguls , cross , half-pipe , slopestyle and big air as well as the alpine version of the skicross . The freestyle skiing world championship is an annual FIS World Championships competition. Freestyle skiing is one of the four disciplines within the winter sports, with ski jumping , Nordic combined and alpine skiing . Freestyle skiing was part of the Olympics since the 1992 Albertville games, but the alpine version is no longer an Olympic event since the 2014 Winter Olympics in Sochi . Freestyle skiing is a relative newcomer to the family of Alpine skiing, being only 38 years old in 2019.

Maximilian II (31 July 1527 – 12 October 1576)  was Holy Roman Emperor from 1564 until his death in 1576. A member of the Austrian House of Habsburg, he was crowned King of Bohemia in Prague on 14 May 1562 and elected King of Germany (King of the Romans) on 24 November 1562. On 8 September 1563 he was crowned King of Hungary and Croatia in the Hungarian capital Pressburg (Pozsony in Hungarian; now Bratislava, Slovakia). On 25 July 1564 he succeeded his father Ferdinand I as ruler of the Holy Roman Empire.Maximilian's rule was shaped by the confessionalization process after the 1555 Peace of Augsburg.

English Renaissance theatre , also known as Renaissance English theatre and Elizabethan theatre , refers to the theatre of England between 1562 and 1642. After the mid-16th century, the theatre of England began to thrive again, this time on a secular basis. A new professional class of playwrights, actors and managers became established in London, and the redevelopment of the Rose playhouse and the Fortune playhouse in the 1590s signalled the beginning of a more stable, permanent theatre building. By the late 1580s, there were 23 different playwrights active in London. The 1590s are considered by many critics to be the zenith of Elizabethan and English Renaissance theatre.

Frederick II of Brandenburg ( 19 November 1413 – 10 February 1471 ) , nicknamed `` the Iron '' (der Eiserne ), was the ruler of Electoral Brandenburg (1440–1470) in the Holy Roman Empire . As de facto ruler, he was one of two main contenders to the title of German King ( the other being his cousin King Sigismund ), but his early death prevented him from assuming the title. However, after his death, the Electors chose his son as the next ruler and he ascended the German throne.

Bacillus cereus is a Gram-positive , rod-shaped , facultatively anaerobic , motile , beta-hemolytic , spore-forming bacterium commonly found in the soil, dust, air, vegetation and water, and is also found in food and the gut of humans and other animals. B. cereus bacteria are often found on cooked foods and are usually present in low numbers on raw foods that are contaminated during preparation or storage. They are particularly associated with foods that have been cooked or reheated before serving, as they can survive for several hours at temperatures above 50°C.

Algebraic topology is a branch of mathematics that uses tools from abstract algebra to study topological spaces . The basic problems of algebraic topology are the calculation of homology groups, which measure the ability of an object to be deformed or stretched into another one, and the determination of homotopy equivalence , a stronger requirement that measures the ability to be deformed into another object. Not to be confused with Matrix algebra. ## Background

Main article: Category theory

In mathematics it is often the case that a more abstract setting is simpler to work in than the concrete setting.

By an Act of February 1, it also requires disbandment of foreign troops in Ireland. January 26 – The Republic of Venice, Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth and Holy Roman Empire sign the Treaty of Karlowitz with the Ottoman Empire, marking an end to the major phase of the Ottoman–Habsburg wars, including the Morean War between Venice and the Ottomans.

June 15 – Battle of Fimreite: King Sverre of Norway defeats and kills his rival, Magnus V (Erlingsson) near Fimreite. Sverre takes the throne and becomes sole ruler of Norway (until 1202).

The history of Anguilla runs from the beginning of human habitation, probably via settlement from South America, through its colonization by the English in the early modern period, to the present day. Following a series of rebellions and a short-lived period as an independent republic during the 1960s, Anguilla has been a separate British overseas territory since 1980.Pre-Columbian AnguillaThe earliest inhabitants of Anguilla were Amerindian people from South America, commonly (if imprecisely) referred to as Arawaks. These people travelled to the island on rafts and in dugout canoes, settling in fishing, hunting and farming groups.

In mathematics, two sets are said to be disjoint sets if they have no element in common. Equivalently, two disjoint sets are sets whose intersection is the empty set. For example, {1, 2, 3} and {4, 5, 6} are disjoint sets, while {1, 2, 3} and {3, 4, 5} are not disjoint. A collection of more than two sets is called disjoint if any two distinct sets of the collection are disjoint.GeneralizationsThis definition of disjoint sets can be extended to a family of sets : the family is pairwise disjoint, or mutually disjoint if  whenever .

Year 1445 ( MCDXLV ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. 1396 – Ottoman–Mamluk War (1421–22): A Crusader army under Jean II de Clisson is crushed in Palestine by Sultan of Egypt, Barsbay. 1400 – Battle of Pochun: General Yi Seong-gye, later to be King Sejong, unifies all of Korea. 1437 – Wars of Alexander I of Epirus: A Byzantine army under John Arkoudilas and Demetrios Kantakouzenos decisively defeats a revolting army under Peter Laskaris at Neopatras.

Only the Duchy of Gaeta remains out of his grasp. Rainulf Drengot, head of a mercenary band of Norman knights, is approached by Duke John V of Gaeta and is persuaded to change sides. With Norman help, Duke Sergius IV recovers Naples from Capuan occupation.

Year 1169 ( MCLXIX ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. 1169 – Battle of Uhud: The Umayyad gains victory over the Alids. 1219 – Mongol-Jin War: Mongol–Jin War: The Mongols and their allies under Ögedei Khan defeat the Jurchen Jin dynasty under Emperor Wu Xing at the Battle of Caishi on the Yangtze River, effectively ending the latter dynasty. The Jurchens withdraw further north to Kaifeng (which they sack in 1232) while the Mongols install a khan of a puppet regime in the former Jin capital.

Edmund of Abingdon (also known as  Edmund Rich, St Edmund of Canterbury, Edmund of Pontigny, French: St Edme; c. 11741240) was an English-born prelate who served as Archbishop of Canterbury. He became a respected lecturer in mathematics, dialectics and theology at the Universities of Paris and Oxford, promoting the study of Aristotle. Having already an unsought reputation as an ascetic, he was ordained a priest, took a doctorate in divinity and soon became known not only for his lectures on theology but as a popular preacher, spending long years travelling within England, and engaging in 1227 preaching the sixth crusade.

It is the fourth university in the English-speaking world and Scotland's fourth oldest university (after the University of St. Andrews, University of Aberdeen and University of Edinburgh).

Year 1175 (MCLXXV) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  England  King Henry II begins living openly with his mistress Rosamund Clifford, raising suspicions about their relationship and alienating Henry's wife, Queen Eleanor of Aquitaine. Eleanor of Aquitaine is held under house arrest at Old Sarum Castle in Wiltshire. She is kept in comfort there – fine clothes for her are dispatched regularly from London. Treaty of Windsor: High King Ruaidrí Ua Conchobair (or Roderic O'Conner) relinquishes his title and agrees to submit to Henry II as vassal of Connacht in Ireland.

Political identity came to the territory now occupied by the Principality of Liechtenstein in 814 , with the formation of the County of Regensberg, a county that also included the territory that now makes up Switzerland . The Crown Lands were passed over to the ownership of Habsburg , the Holy Roman Emperor in 1322. The Crown Lands then remained in Habsburg possession until the reign of Emperor Joseph II in the eighteenth century. He, in the name of centralization, grouped all of the lands held by the Habsburg family together, and on 29 May 1806 created the Austrian Empire .

The Khlysts or Khlysty ( , `` whips '' ) were an underground Spiritual Christian sect , which split from the Russian Orthodox Church at the beginning of the 18th century . Khlysty (whips) were named thus because they flagellated themselves until bleeding in order to attain religious ecstasy , and were also known in some places as the Kukhlysts (whipping ones). In 1700 the Khlysts were divided into two sects, that of the Dukhobory (the spirit wrestlers ) and that of the Molokan (milk drinkers), the latter remaining more faithful to traditional Orthodox doctrine.

Microware was a US corporation based in Clive , Iowa that produced the OS-9 real-time operating system.Microware Systems Corporation existed as two separate corporations: the first, Microware Systems Corporation in the US and Canada; and the second Microware Systems Limited in Europe. In 1992 the two companies were merged to become Microware Inc., which was then purchased by Echelon Corporation in 2001. MicroWorlds is a visual programming language from LC Technology International, Inc that allows users to create multimedia, educational, and business software. MicroWorlds has been used for a wide variety of software projects, ranging from games to simulations and modeling tools.

In the Swedish calendar it began as a leap year starting on Monday and remained so until Thursday , February 10 when Swedish authorities decided to fix the discrepancy by inserting an extra day. In , the Swedish calendar was reformed from the Julian calendar to the Gregorian calendar, by skipping eleven days, from 18 February to 2 March. This was done in accordance with the calendar reform of the neighboring countries, Denmark , Norway and Finland , but not with that of its neighbor Poland. In Sweden , as in most other countries of Western Europe , 1 January was always the start of the New Year.

Adrian of Nicomedia ( also known as Hadrian ) or Saint Adrian ( , died 4 March 306 ) was the son of Eubulus and Pemonia, the governor of Cappadocia during the reign of Maximian . He is considered a martyr and is celebrated on 8 March. According to the Passion by Saint Ambrose , Hadrian was born in Rome, the son of Euboulos and Pemonia . Euboulos was from the city of Nicomedia (modern-day Gelibolu , Turkey ) , and had served as governor of Cappadocia, but had been removed from office for treason.

Dyson 's eternal intelligence concept ( the Dyson Scenario ) , proposed by Freeman Dyson in 1979 , proposes a situation in which eternal life is possible for intelligent civilizations through the process of recursive self-modification or eternal self-replication . 1 This would be possible because the increasing power of computation and the increasing speed of innovation would make it easier and easier to build machines that were smarter and more capable than themselves. This would make it possible for these super-intelligent beings to transform themselves into entities that are even more capable than their ancestors, and so on.

Events March 18 – Jacques de Molay , the 23rd and last Grand Master of the Knights Templar , is burned at the stake, after he recants his claims that the charges brought against the Templars were unjust. Heinrich Christian Wilhelm Busch ( 15 April 1832 – 9 January 1908 ) was a German humorist , poet , illustrator , graphic artist , and painter whose work as an illustrator and author influenced 20 th century popular culture. He is known as “der Büchermensch” (the man of the books), a character he himself had drawn. He was one of the best known proponents of the artistic and literary Jugendstil and its most famous German writer. His verses and his images became widely known throughout the world during his life time and even today.

The County of Toulouse is returned to the crown of France.

Otto III ( June/July 980 – 23 January 1002 ) was Holy Roman Emperor from 996 until his early death. A member of the Saxon dynasty, Otto III was the oldest son of the late Emperor Otto II and was crowned Otto II's successor after helping his father in Italy. However, Otto II had died before he could return to Germany, and Otto III was a child of eight when he was crowned in 983. Thus the government was led by his mother, the Empress Theophanu (955-991), his aunt Sophia (955-991) and Adalbert, Margrave of Meissen (928-982/83).

A playwright or dramatist is a person who writes plays.EtymologyThe word "play" is from Middle English pleye, from Old English plæġ, pleġa, plæġa ("play, exercise; sport, game; drama, applause"). The word "wright" is an archaic English term for a craftsman or builder (as in a wheelwright or cartwright). The words combine to indicate a person who has "wrought" words, themes, and other elements into a dramatic form—a play. (The homophone with "write" is coincidental.

Ernest Orlando Lawrence (August 8, 1901 – August 27, 1958) was a pioneering American nuclear scientist and winner of the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1939 for his invention of the cyclotron. He is known for his work on uranium-isotope separation for the Manhattan Project, as well as for founding the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory and the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.A graduate of the University of South Dakota and University of Minnesota, Lawrence obtained a PhD in physics at Yale in 1925. In 1928, he was hired as an associate professor of physics at the University of California, Berkeley, becoming the youngest full professor there two years later.

Nvidia Corporation  is an American multinational technology company incorporated in Delaware and based in Santa Clara, California. It is a fabless company which designs graphics processing units (GPUs) for the gaming and professional markets, as well as system on a chip units (SoCs) for the mobile computing and automotive market. Its primary GPU line, labeled "GeForce", is in direct competition with the GPUs of the "Radeon" brand by Advanced Micro Devices (AMD). Nvidia expanded its presence in the gaming industry with its handheld game consoles Shield Portable, Shield Tablet, and Shield Android TV and its cloud gaming service GeForce Now.

Bamboos are a diverse group of evergreen perennial flowering plants in the subfamily Bambusoideae of the grass family Poaceae. Giant bamboos are the largest members of the grass family. The origin of the word "bamboo" is uncertain, but it probably comes from the Dutch or Portuguese language, which originally borrowed it from Malay or Kannada.In bamboo, as in other grasses, the internodal regions of the stem are usually hollow and the vascular bundles in the cross-section are scattered throughout the stem instead of in a cylindrical arrangement. The dicotyledonous woody xylem is also absent.

Dissociative identity disorder (DID), previously known as multiple personality disorder (MPD), is a mental disorder characterized by the maintenance of at least two distinct and relatively enduring personality states. The disorder is accompanied by memory gaps beyond what would be explained by ordinary memory issues. The personality states alternately show in a person's behavior; however, presentations of the disorder vary. Other conditions that often occur in people with DID include post-traumatic stress disorder, personality disorders (especially borderline and avoidant), depression, substance use disorders, conversion disorder, somatic symptom disorder, eating disorders, obsessive–compulsive disorder, and sleep disorders.

Maximilian II ( 31 July 1527 – 12 October 1576 ) was Holy Roman Emperor from 1564 until his death. Maximilian was born at Vienna, the son of Ferdinand I, Holy Roman Emperor, and Anne of Bohemia and Hungary. In 1551 he married his cousin Maria of Spain. The marriage was not a success, and in 1559 they were officially separated. The same year he married his true love, the beautiful Hungarian countess (and widow of his former imperial chamberlain) Agnes Habsburg. This union produced three children: Ferdinand, Margaretha (who died at age 7) and Ernst (who died young).

The Khlysts or Khlysty (,  "whips") were an underground Spiritual Christian sect, which split from the Russian Orthodox Church and existed from the 1600s until the late 20th century.NameThe members of the sect referred to themselves by various names, including "God's People" (liudi bozh'i), "followers of Christ's faith" (Khristovovery), or simply "Christs" (Khristy). The appellation "Khlysty" is a derogatory term applied by critics of the sect. The origin of the term is disputed.

Mai Elisabeth Zetterling ( ; 24 May 1925 – 17 March 1994 ) was a Swedish actress , novelist and theatre director . Zetterling appeared in more than sixty films between 1941 and 1993 . She won four Guldbagge Awards and was nominated for the European Film Award for Best Actress for The Emigrants (1971) . The latter film is one of the two Swedish films that received the Golden Bear award at the Berlin International Film Festival . She was the second Swedish actress in history, after Zarah Leander in the late 1930s, to be nominated for a Golden Globe .

Norwich is a town in Windsor County , in the U.S. state of Vermont . The population was 3,612 at the 2000 census. It is the home of the longest covered bridge (3,450 feet (1,052 m) long, 128 feet (39 m) wide and over 184 feet (56 m) tall) in the United States . Norwich University is the oldest private military academy in the country, founded in 1819 and located in Norwich. Norwich University is also home to one of the first and oldest Reserve Officers Training Corps (ROTC) in the United States .

Gravity , or gravitation , is a natural phenomenon by which all things with mass or energy , including planets , stars and galaxies , are brought toward one another. Gravity is the most weak of the four basic forces of nature , yet has an influence over much of the universe because of its universal character. The gravitational attraction of the Sun keeps the Earth and the other planets in orbit around it, and similarly, the gravity of planets keeps satellites , comets and asteroids in motion. Gravity was first explored by early Greek philosophers and was first explained by Isaac Newton , who developed his theory of universal gravitation .

Johan August Arfwedson ( 12 January 1792 – 28 October 1841 ) was a Swedish chemist who discovered the chemical element lithium, in 1817. [1][2][3][4][5][6][7] He was a professor at Uppsala University. He discovered the first known compound of lithium, which is lithium carbonate. [8]

2.1 Other chemical elements
Johan Arfwedsson was born 12 January 1792 in Uppsala, Sweden. His father, Anders Jonas Arfwedsson, was a Lutheran priest.

May 30 – Hussite Wars – Battle of Lipany: The Catholics and Ultraquists defeat the Taborites, ending the Hussite Wars. June 19 or 20 – Zara Yaqob becomes Emperor of Ethiopia. Late June – Miner Engelbrekt Engelbrektsson begins a Swedish rebellion against King Eric of Pomerania (named the Engelbrekt rebellion after him), eventually leading to the deposition of the king.

Year 1514 (MDXIV) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 10 – A great fire breaks out, in the Rialto of Venice. March 12 – A huge exotic embassy sent by King Manuel I of Portugal to Pope Leo X arrives in Rome, including Hanno, an Indian elephant. March – Louis XII of France makes peace with Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor. May 2 – The Poor Conrad peasant revolt against Ulrich, Duke of Württemberg begins in Beutelsbach.

Salvador Domingo Felipe Jacinto Dalí i Domènech, 1st Marquess of Dalí of Púbol  (; ; ; 11 May 190423 January 1989) was a Spanish surrealist artist renowned for his technical skill, precise draftsmanship, and the striking and bizarre images in his work.Born in Figueres, Catalonia, Spain, Dalí received his formal education in fine arts in Madrid. Influenced by Impressionism and the Renaissance masters from a young age, he became increasingly attracted to Cubism and avant-garde movements. He moved closer to Surrealism in the late 1920s and joined the Surrealist group in 1929, soon becoming one of its leading exponents.

Year 1413 (MCDXIII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  March 21 – Henry V becomes King of England following the death of his father Henry IV. July 5 – Battle of Çamurlu: Mehmed I defeats his brother Musa, ending the Ottoman Interregnum. August 28 – The University of St Andrews in Scotland is chartered by papal bull. October 2 – The Kingdom of Poland and Grand Duchy of Lithuania sign the Union of Horodło.Date unknown  Samogitia becomes the last region in Europe to be Christianized.

The Air Ministry was a department of the Government of the United Kingdom with the responsibility of managing the affairs of the Royal Air Force, that existed from 1918 to 1964. It was under the political authority of the Secretary of State for Air.Organisations before the Air MinistryThe Air CommitteeOn 13 April 1912, less than two weeks after the creation of the Royal Flying Corps (which initially consisted of both a naval and a military wing), an Air Committee was established to act as an intermediary between the Admiralty and the War Office in matters relating to aviation.

Aloysius Lilius (c. 1510 – 1576), also variously referred to as Luigi Lilio, Luigi Giglio, was an Italian doctor, astronomer, philosopher and chronologist, and also the "primary author" who provided the proposal that (after modifications) became the basis of the Gregorian Calendar reform of 1582.The crater Lilius on the Moon is named after him, as is the asteroid 2346 Lilio. In computer science, the Lilian date is the number of days since the adoption of the Gregorian calendar on 15 October 1582.Life and workNot much is known about the early life of Lilius/Lilio/Giglio.

Anne Boleyn ( ; 1501 – 19 May 1536 ) was Queen of England from 1533 to 1536 , as the second wife of King Henry VIII and Marrige to the Catholic king Henry Tudor of England ended with her execution on charges of high treason and adultery . A daughter of the prominent Boleyn family from East Anglia, Anne came to the court of Henry VIII at the age of fourteen, and became a maid of honour two years later. The king’s chief minister, Thomas Wolsey, arranged her 1522 marriage to the Crown Prince of Portugal.

Year 1408 (MCDVIII) was a leap year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  February 19 – Battle of Bramham Moor: A royalist army defeats the last remnants of the Percy Rebellion. September – Henry, Prince of Wales (later Henry V of England) retakes Aberystwyth from Owain Glyndŵr. September 16 – Thorstein Olafssøn marries Sigrid Bjørnsdatter in Hvalsey Church, in the last recorded event of the Norse history of Greenland. December 5 – Emir Edigu of Golden Horde reaches Moscow. December 13 – The Order of the Dragon is founded under King Sigismund of Hungary.

Gregory agrees to lift the excommunication against Henry. 13th – Henry IV is received by Gregory VII.

Moore's law is the observation that the number of transistors in a dense integrated circuit (IC) doubles about every two years. Moore's law is an observation and projection of a historical trend. Rather than a law of physics, it is an empirical relationship linked to gains from experience in production.The observation is named after Gordon Moore, the co-founder of Fairchild Semiconductor and Intel (and former CEO of the latter), who in 1965 posited a doubling every year in the number of components per integrated circuit, and projected this rate of growth would continue for at least another decade.

Provincetown  is a New England town located at the extreme tip of Cape Cod in Barnstable County, Massachusetts, in the United States. A small coastal resort town with a year-round population of 3,664 as of the 2020 United States Census, Provincetown has a summer population as high as 60,000. Often called "P-town" or "P'town", the locale is known for its beaches, harbor, artists, tourist industry, and as a popular vacation destination for the LGBT+ community.History At the time of European encounter, the area was long settled by the historic Nauset tribe, who had a settlement known as "Meeshawn".

1581 ( MDLXXXI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Julian calendar . April 13 – The Colonial Virginia Assembly passes a law requiring free or indentured residents of the Colony to have their servants wear a red mark on their left shoulder. April 26 – Sir Walter Raleigh is released from the Tower of London after being a prisoner for 13 years. June 24 – The Colony of Roanoke is founded. November 9 – Sir Francis Drake is knighted in London by Queen Elizabeth I . November 11 – An earthquake hits Skopelos and surrounding islands in Greece.

Louis I, also Louis the Great (; ; ) or Louis the Hungarian (; 5 March 132610 September 1382), was King of Hungary and Croatia from 1342 and King of Poland from 1370. He was the first child of Charles I of Hungary and his wife, Elizabeth of Poland, to survive infancy. A 1338 treaty between his father and Casimir III of Poland, Louis's maternal uncle, confirmed Louis's right to inherit the Kingdom of Poland if his uncle died without a son. In exchange, Louis was obliged to assist his uncle to reoccupy the lands that Poland had lost in previous decades.

Year 1318 ( MCCCXVIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. 1318 (MCCCXVIII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar. October 20 - Battle of Morgarten: The St. Gallen citizen's army defeats the Habsburg forces, leading to the independence of Switzerland. December 6 - The Treaty of Northampton restores the Kingdom of England to its 1284 limits after the Scottish War of Independence (1296 - 1328), which included the English conquests of Wales and Northern Ireland.

Year 1059 (MLIX) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  November 22 – Emperor Isaac I Komnenos falls ill on a hunt and retires to a monastery after a 2-year reign. He abdicates the Byzantine throne and appoints Constantine X, a Paphlagonian nobleman, as his successor. Fall – The Magyars cross the Danube River, together with several Pecheneg tribes, but are halted by Byzantine forces (approximate date). Europe  Peter Krešimir IV (the Great) is crowned king of Croatia and Dalmatia.

McLean Hospital ( formerly known as Somerville Asylum and Charlestown Asylum ) is a psychiatric hospital in Belmont , Massachusetts , about seven miles northwest of Boston. It is located on a 22-acre campus on the Charles River. McLean is the largest psychiatric facility of Harvard Medical School , which in turn is affiliated with McLean. The McLean campus includes the 282-bed hospital, 24-bed residential home ( McLean House ), 90-bed McLean North Residence, McLean's Child and Family Center, the 211-bed Watkins Memory Care Center, and several outpatient clinic facilities. The current hospital opened in 1976.

Year 1422 (MCDXXII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 10 – Hussite Wars – Battle of Deutschbrod: The Hussites defeat 2,000 Royalist Crusaders. March 21–May 2 – Hundred Years' War – Siege of Meaux: Meaux surrenders to the English. June 10–September – The Ottoman sultan Murad II besieges Constantinople; the siege is broken off as a result of the rebellion of Küçük Mustafa. August 22 – Use of the Spanish era dating system in the Kingdom of Portugal ceases.

Year 1169 (MCLXIX) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Late Summer – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) sends an embassy to Egypt to demand tribute, and threatens the country with war when they refuse to pay it. The Byzantine fleet under Admiral Andronikos Kontostephanos sets out from the Hellespont; 60 war galleys are sent to Palestine. with money for "the knights of Jerusalem". Andronikos with the rest of the fleet sails to Cyprus, at which he defeats a patrolling squadron of 6 Fatimid ships.

A noble savage is a literary stock character who embodies the concept of the indigene , outsider , wild human , or "other" who is not yet corrupted by civilization . The concept of "the noble savage" is associated with the Enlightenment belief that all people are born "noble and ignorant" and that their behaviour is determined by their external circumstances, such as the presence or absence of a civilizing society, or more generally their geographical location, race or class. The noble savage lives in a natural state in forests, plains, or mountainous regions.

Year 1301 (MCCCI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January 14 – The death of Andrew III of Hungary ends the Árpád Dynasty in Hungary, resulting in a power struggle between Wenceslaus III of Bohemia, Otto III, Duke of Bavaria, and Charles Robert of Naples. February 7 – Edward of Caernarvon (later King Edward II of England) becomes the first Prince of Wales. March 3 – Emperor Go-Nijō succeeds Emperor Go-Fushimi on the throne of Japan.

Prince Igor  is an opera in four acts with a prologue, written and composed by Alexander Borodin. The composer adapted the libretto from the Ancient Russian epic The Lay of Igor's Host, which recounts the campaign of Rus' prince Igor Svyatoslavich against the invading Cuman ("Polovtsian") tribes in 1185. He also incorporated material drawn from two medieval Kievan chronicles. The opera was left unfinished upon the composer's death in 1887 and was edited and completed by Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov and Alexander Glazunov. It was first performed in St. Petersburg, Russia, in 1890.

Year 1482 (MCDLXXXII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 19 – A Portuguese fleet, commanded by Diogo de Azambuja, arrives at the mouth of the River Benya on the Gold Coast, where the fort of São Jorge da Mina (Elmina Castle) is erected. January 25 – Probable first printing of the Torah, in Bologna. February 28 –The village of Alhama de Granada in Spain is taken by Christian forces, starting the Granada War to expel the Moors from the Iberian Peninsula back to Africa.

Aloysius Lilius ( c. 1510 – 1576 ) , also variously referred to as Luigi Lilio , Luigi Giglio , or Aloisius Lilio, is often noted as the first person to correctly suggest the Gregorian calendar. Astrologer , mathematician and physician, he studied at the University of Bologna and the University of Padua , and then at the University of Pavia where he became professor of mathematics in 1550. There is evidence to suggest he was also in Rome, possibly studying medicine. In 1577, he published the Almanac Perpetuum which included his calendar proposal.

Year 1354 (MCCCLIV) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  Early in the year – Ibn Battuta returns from his travels at the command of Abu Inan Faris, sultan of Morocco, who appoints a scribe to write an account of the adventures. February 12 –  The Treaty of Stralsund settles border disputes between the duchies of Mecklenburg and Pomerania. March 2 –  The Gallipoli earthquake occurs, followed within a month by Turkish capture and settlement (see Fall of Gallipoli).

Banksia is a genus of around 170 species in the plant family Proteaceae. These Australian wildflowers and popular garden plants are easily recognised by their characteristic flower spikes and fruiting "cones" and heads. Banksias range in size from prostrate woody shrubs to trees up to 30 metres (100 ft) tall. They are found in a wide variety of landscapes: sclerophyll forest, (occasionally) rainforest, shrubland, and some more arid landscapes, though not in Australia's deserts.Heavy producers of nectar, banksias are a vital part of the food chain in the Australian bush.

Year 1208 ( MCCVIII ) was a leap year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar . 1095 – The first of many Crusader states are created as the Crusaders re-take Antioch . 1100 – King William II of England dies (struck by an arrow) while hunting in the New Forest. He is succeeded by his brother Henry I. 1179 – Saladin enters Jerusalem after destroying the crusader forces of the Second Crusade . 1258 – Alfonso X is recognized as King of Castile and León. 1294 – King Edward I of England issues the Statute of Ghent .

An engagement ring is a ring indicating that the person wearing it is engaged to be married , especially in Western countries. The ring is offered as a token of love and fidelity by her partner to her and is typically worn on the left ring finger , which is associated with love in many […]
A ring that symbolizes the union and love between a bride and a groom on their marriage day. The ring is given on a specific occasion and time by the groom to the bride in the ceremony of marriage.

Mariner-H ( Mariner Mars '71 ) , also commonly known as Mariner 8 , was ( along with Mariner 9 ) NASA 's second successful Mariner mission designed to orbit Mars and study it from orbit. The probe's mission was plagued by a series of mechanical failures and problems, but was saved from being a total failure by the successful launch of Mariner 9 two weeks later. Mariner-H consisted of an octagonal-shaped protective aeroshell and a spacecraft that measured about 2.9 m x 3.0 m x 1.8 m ( 9.5 x 9.8 x 5.9 ft ) .

Howard Kingsbury Smith ( May 12 , 1914 – February 15 , 2002 ) was an American journalist , radio and television commentator , and television correspondent . He was also a political activist , an international lecturer , and author of the books The Russians and The World That Changed, for which he was later awarded the American Book Award. Born in New Orleans , Louisiana , Smith studied at Tulane University (1931–1933), but did not earn a degree. He earned a BA from Columbia University , and later served as a trustee of Columbia and of its affiliate, Columbia University School of Journalism .

Mariner 10 was an American robotic space probe launched by NASA on 3 November 1973 , to fly by the planet Mercury. It was the first space probe to complete an encounter with the planet Mercury, and is also notable for being the only spacecraft to do so to date (as of late 2010). Messenger is a space probe on a journey to planet Mercury. It was launched on March 12, 2004 and arrived on March 18, 2011 for the first of three flybys. It will spend approximately a year orbiting Mercury. It will pass by again, in October 2013, and March 2015.

Year 1579 ( MDLXXIX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In Sweden, the Kalmar Union, a personal union between the three kingdoms of Denmark, Norway (including Iceland) and Sweden, is replaced by royal unions. Denmark–Norway unites with Norway, while a new Swedish-Polish union is declared. Both of these unions, unlike the old Kalmar Union, are to be ruled by separate monarchs, with the monarchs' titles being decided by local legislation. In Japan, Emperor Ōgimachi succeeds his brother Ōjirō, after a reign of 18 days.

Events January–June January 1 Colonel George Monck ( with his regiment ) crosses from Scotland to England at the village of Saltcoats to help Charles II ( who is in hiding at Newcastle ) return to England. He is joined by Colonel Robert Lilburne, who brings with him 2, 000 men from Ireland. Monck marches his troops through Scotland, gathering more men as he goes. When he arrives in London on January 3, he persuades the Lord Mayor to allow them to march through the streets with drums beating and flags flying to Whitehall Palace to the King's presence, with no opposition.

Charles XIV John (; born Jean Bernadotte; 26 January 1763 – 8 March 1844) was King of Sweden and Norway from 1818 until his death. In modern Norwegian lists of kings he is called Charles III John . He was the first monarch of the Bernadotte dynasty.Born in Pau in southern France, Bernadotte joined the French Royal Army in 1780. Following the outbreak of the French Revolution, he exhibited great military talent, rapidly rising through the ranks, and was made a brigadier general by 1794. He served with distinction in Italy and Germany, and was briefly Minister of War.

The Stoned Guest is a "half-act opera" by Peter Schickele in the satirical persona of P. D. Q. Bach. The title is a play on the "stone guest" character in Don Giovanni by Mozart, as well as the opera The Stone Guest by Alexander Sergeyevich Dargomïzhsky after the play by Pushkin. The work is a parody of classical opera, although some critics consider it to be the equal of many classical works in technical ability. The opera appears on the 1970 album of the same name.The loose story combines elements of Don Giovanni with elements of Carmen by Georges Bizet.

Observations show that the expansion of the universe is accelerating , such that the velocity at which a distant galaxy is receding today is larger than the velocity of the same galaxy 10 billion years ago. This fact poses a major problem in modern cosmology, since it cannot be accommodated by the laws of gravity that are observed in the Solar System. The expansion of our universe cannot be understood using Einstein’s General Relativity as the theory has to be modified to include a repulsive force and a new form of dark matter or dark energy.

Bamboos are a diverse group of evergreen perennial flowering plants in the subfamily Bambusoideae of the grass family Poaceae . The bamboo is one of the fastest growing plants in the world. A single bamboo plant can grow up to 1 inch in 3 hours! They can live for more than a century and reach a height of 30 metres. There are many uses of bamboo and many reasons for growing them. They are very strong, easy to grow and have a variety of uses. Why grow Bamboo? There are three main reasons you should consider growing bamboos:
They can prevent erosion of your soil.

Ernest Orlando Lawrence ( August 8 , 1901 – August 27 , 1958 ) was a pioneering American nuclear scientist , physical chemist and Nobel Laureate . Lawrence received the 1939 Nobel Prize in physics for his work on uranium . He directed the first laboratory in the United States to successfully refine uranium metal for use in the Manhattan Project , where his team developed the process of gaseous diffusion and the cyclotron . Lawrence also served as a consultant to the US Army Corps of Engineers during the war. He was also known as a champion of big science .

Events  January–June  January 18 – François, Duke of Anjou, attacks Antwerp. February 4 – Gebhard Truchsess von Waldburg, newly converted to Calvinism, formally marries Agnes von Mansfeld-Eisleben, a former canoness of Gerresheim, while retaining his position as Archbishop-Elector of Cologne. March 10 – The Queen Elizabeth's Men troupe of actors is ordered to be founded in England. May – Battle of Shizugatake in Japan: Shibata Katsuie is defeated by Toyotomi Hideyoshi, who goes on to commence construction of Osaka Castle. May 22 – Ernest of Bavaria is elected as Roman Catholic Archbishop of Cologne, in opposition to Gebhard Truchsess von Waldburg.

September 11–12 – Isaac II (Angelos) leads a revolt in Constantinople and deposes Emperor Andronikos I (Komnenos).
