Renate Titzia Groenewold ( born 8 October 1976 ) is a Dutch former long track speed skater and road bicycle racer . She won two medals at the 1998 Winter Olympic Games in Nagano . In 1999 she became world champion all-round speed skating . The same year she left speed skating . In 2001 she took up road bicycle racing and won a bronze medal at the 2003 UCI Road World Cup . She competed in three summer Olympics in the road bicycle races . She won a bronze medal in the team time trial event at the 2012 Summer Olympics in London .

Year 990 ( CMXC ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. 1015–1022 – The reign of Cnut the Great is considered the end of the Old English era of English history, as well as the beginning of the Danish era. Although Cnut was a Dane, he ruled over both England and Norway, and was seen by contemporaries to be an ideal king. 1022–1023 – The reigns of Cnut the Great, his son Harthacnut (in England only), and his grandson Magnus the Good.

In mathematics , open sets are a generalization of open intervals in the real line . In a metric space—that is, a space that has a notion of distance—an open set is simply a set for which every pair of points has a distance between them. In topological spaces and vector spaces, there are stronger conditions for a set to be an open set. For open sets in algebra, see Open subset. Open sets are an example of a topology. ## Definition

In the real numbers, every open interval of the form (a,b) is an open set.

In computational complexity theory , PSPACE is the set of all decision problems that can be solved by a Turing machine using space polynomial in the input size and random access memory polynomial in the number of possible solutions. In the context of Turing machines with an unbounded tape , PSPACE is the set of decision problems solvable by a Turing machine that has unbounded read-only storage, and write-only storage bounded by a polynomial function of the size of the tape (whereas the tape may be infinitely long). The term PSPACE is an acronym for Polynomial-sized Space , but it has become so common that its expansion is not needed.

Botulinum toxin (BoNT) is a neurotoxic protein produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum and related species. It prevents the release of the neurotransmitter acetylcholine from axon endings at the neuromuscular junction, thus causing flaccid paralysis. The toxin causes the disease botulism. The toxin is also used commercially for medical and cosmetic purposes.The seven main types of botulinum toxin are named types A to G (A, B, C1, C2, D, E, F and G). New types are occasionally found. Types A and B are capable of causing disease in humans, and are also used commercially and medically.

Year 1024 ( MXXIV ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Year 1024 ( MXXIV ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. ... Events February 21 - Concordat of Worms: Emperor Heinrich II agrees to support the Pope as his feudal superior, in return for political support in northern Italy. Emperor Otto III of Germany is deposed by his mother Theophano and her cousin, the Count of Holland, Dietrich von Katlenburg.

In category theory , a branch of mathematics , the abstract notion of a limit captures the essential properties of the limit point of a sequence or net . A limit point may be defined for any infinite set of points. The most common definition of the limit point is in terms of convergence . If the sequence or net is converging to some point , the points which are converging to the limit point from the right and the limit point itself can be called its limit points. In this way one can define two kinds of limits on a sequence or net of points in a topological space .

Year 1446 ( MCDXLVI ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. 1546 (MDXLVII) was a common year starting on Thursday ( dominical letter G ) of the Julian calendar. 1546 ( MDLXVI ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( dominical letter D ) of the Julian calendar. 1216 – The Battle of Sandwich takes place in the harbour at Sandwich, Kent, during the Baron's War. English naval forces under William Longsword defeat a French invasion fleet.

The Air Ministry was a department of the Government of the United Kingdom with the responsibility of managing the affairs of the Royal Air Force (RAF), which included the maintenance of aerodromes, the supply of aircraft, equipment, and stores, the training of aircrews, and the formulation of operational doctrine. It was also responsible for the procurement of aircraft from aircraft manufacturers and the operation and maintenance of the RAF Depots. Its headquarters was located in the Air Ministry Building in Victoria, London, adjacent to Birdcage Walk opposite the Horse Guards. The Ministry existed from April 1918 to 1964.

Year 1526 (MDXXVI) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 14 – Treaty of Madrid: Peace is declared between Francis I of France and Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor. Francis agrees to cede Burgundy and abandons all claims to Flanders, Artois, Naples, and Milan. April 21 – Battle of Panipat: Babur becomes Mughal emperor, invades northern India and captures Delhi, beginning the richest dynasty in the world, the Mughal Empire, which lasts until 1857.

Photomontage is the process and the result of making a composite photograph by cutting , gluing , rearranging and overlapping images, either to produce new meanings or to mock or criticize the photographic depictions of the world. Today, the term is generally used for a two-dimensional work of art combining photographs, drawings, letters, or other elements and objects, but the term in its original sense can also be applied to photomontage works constructed using only photographs. Typically such works are seen as less serious, more decorative and less innovative works of art than those produced by straight photography.

Arthur Andersen LLP was an American holding company based in Chicago . Formerly one of the `` Big Five '' audit firms, it was founded by Arthur Andersen and Frank Thornton in 1913. The company was renamed in 1997 as Andersen Consulting after its core division was spun off as an independent company. In the 2001–2005 Enron audit scandal, it was found that staff at Arthur Andersen had destroyed many of Enron's documents, which led to the company being charged with obstruction of justice. The scandal also led to Arthur Andersen being disbanded by court order.

Albert III ( 9 November 141411 March 1486 ) was Elector of Brandenburg from 1471 until his death , the last to rule from both the Hohenzollern and Margraviate of Brandenburg . As he died without issue, his territories passed to his nephew, Elector Joachim II, who also united Brandenburg with the Margraviate of Ansbach . Early life . Albert was born at the Margraviate of Meissen, the eldest son of Frederick II, Margrave of Meissen by his second marriage to Katharina of Schwarzburg (daughter of Günther XXXVIII, Count of Schwarzburg-Sondershausen ).

Year 1151 (MCLI) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  September 7 – Geoffrey of Anjou dies, and is succeeded by his son Henry, aged 18. After the Battle of Ghazni, the city is burned by the Prince of Ghur. The first plague and fire insurance policy is issued in Iceland. Bolton Abbey is founded in North Yorkshire, England. Anping Bridge is completed in China's Fujian province. Its total length will not be exceeded until 1846.

Year 1366 ( MCCCLXVI ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. 1366 – John Wycliffe becomes the first Oxford professor to be dismissed from his post. 1366 ( MCCCLXVI )was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. 1366 - John Wycliffe becomes the first Oxford professor to be dismissed from his post. Tone is the use of pitch in language to distinguish lexical or grammatical meaning – that is, to distinguish or to inflect words. All verbal languages use pitch to express emotional and other paralinguistic information and to convey emphasis, contrast and other such features in what is called intonation, but not all languages use tones to distinguish words or their inflections, analogously to consonants and vowels. Languages that have this feature are called tonal languages; the distinctive tone patterns of such a language are sometimes called tonemes, by analogy with phoneme.

During the 1920s and 1930s, jazz flourished as a popular music form and helped define the culture of American cities during the period between World War I and the Depression. It was called the Jazz Age.

Symbiosis (from Greek , , "living together", from , , "together", and , bíōsis, "living") is any type of a close and long-term biological interaction between two different biological organisms, be it mutualistic, commensalistic, or parasitic. The organisms, each termed a symbiont, must be of different species. In 1879, Heinrich Anton de Bary defined it as "the living together of unlike organisms". The term was subject to a century-long debate about whether it should specifically denote mutualism, as in lichens.
